INSERT INTO `cat3` VALUES (1,'one to one','There are two networks inter-connected. Each node of each network is inter-connected with exactly one node in the other network. If a node fails the corresponding part also fails. The number of nodes in each network is the same. The inter and intra interactions are bidirectional (non-directed). A node is considered functional if it belongs to the largest connected component.'),(2,'two-layer network model','This model has a client network and an optical transport network. The client layer is connected via UNIs (User Network Interface) to the OTN (Optical Transport Network). The control planes of both layers exchange no information (overlay model) or only sparse information (augmented model) about the current routing and resource usage. The client layer can request new link capacities on demand from the OTN-provider dynamically, using the UNI. Thus, the main concept of the client is to adjust the link resources automatically and cost-efficiently depending on the current demand.'),(3,'overlay model','There is a substrate network considered fixed (physical), a logical topology (logic) and on top of that there\'s the overlay network or overlay mapping. Overlay mapping is defined here as the process of mapping an application request to a substrate network whilst satisfying the specific requirements of the application. '),(4,'compressed one to one','This model takes the same kind of interactions as a one-to-one model but compresses the 2two networks into one network that captures the behaviour of the original coupled pair. Here if 2 nodes av in N1 and u in N2 are interconected, in the compressed version will be represented as uxv and any edge that u or v had will remain. In this model, unlike one to one, there can be uncoupled nodes. In this compressed network is direct that if a node fails its interdependent node also fails.'),(5,'one to one weighted','The interactions are equal to the one to one model. There are two networks inter-connected. Each node of each network is inter-connected with exactly one node in the other network. If a node fails the corresponding part also fails. The number of nodes in each network is the same. The inter and intra interactions are bidirectional (non-directed). Each node, intra and inter-edge have a weight. If 1-t is the probability that one node in network A fails, then the probability that one edge in network A is present is equal to t*t. For the inter-edge case the probability is t since it only depends on a node of network A not failing. Only nodes in network A can fail.'),(6,'multiple support-dependence with load','This model describe relations between networks where a node in one network depends on one or more nodes in the other network. This dependence is unidirectional. The dependent node must have at least one support node in order to function. Nodes and links have weight and nodes have capacities. Here there are flows of packages from (to) each node and if a node fails then the load is redistributed by the new weight of each node and link. The weight of links is given as a function of intra-degree or inter-degree of the nodes connected by the link. The inter-degree of a node is given by the amount of nodes on the other network that support it. The weight/load of a node corresponds to the betweenness centrality of the node since each package uses the shortest path.'),(7,'Spatial one to one','The interactions between networks are the same as in the one to one model (bidirectional dependence). Inside the network links are non directed too. In this model not all the nodes of a network are necessarily connected. There is a \'distance\' between nodes given by the \'length\' of the link. This length exist thanks to the spatial embedding of the network (nodes have spatial coordinates). Two nodes acan get inter-connected (1 node in net. A 1 node in net. B) only if they are at a distance of at most r. If r=0 then the case is that of a single network and if r=inf then the interconnections aare simply usual connections at random.'),(8,'one to one with lifetime','There are two networks inter-connected. Each node of each network is inter-connected with exactly one node in the other network. If a node fails the corresponding part also fails. The number of nodes in each network is the same. The inter and intra interactions are bidirectional (non-directed). The components have a \'lifetime\' after which they begin to fail. The overall interdependent network  also has a lifetime. The interdependent-network lifetime is given by the time where \'\'criticality is reached\'\' (destruction/p_c).'),(9,'unidiectional bipartite PG-CCN','This model considers 2 interdependent networks that don\'t posses intra-intercations. The networks specifically represent the Power Grid network (PG) and the Control and Communication Network (CCN). On the PG there are Generators and Substations but only substations conform the actual models since it\'s assumed that each substation is connected to the generator and to cut an edge is equal to say that the subst. node failed. On the CCN there are Control Centers and Routers, the case is analogous to the PG. Here the dependencies between subst. and routers may be multiple and are unidirectional.'),(10,'bidirectional bipartite PG-CCN','This model considers 2 interdependent networks that don\'t posses intra-intercations. The networks specifically represent the Power Grid network (PG) and the Control and Communication Network (CCN). On the PG there are Generators and Substations but only substations conform the actual models since it\'s assumed that each substation is connected to the generator and to cut an edge is equal to say that the subst. node failed. On the CCN there are Control Centers and Routers, the case is analogous to the PG. Here the dependencies between subst. and routers may be multiple and are biderctional.'),(11,'non-exclusive one to one','This model present the same interactions and type of cascading failures as the one to one model. Except that in this case each node may be interconnected with one or more nodes in the other network. A node remains functional if it is connected to the largest connected component and if at least one of its inter-dependent nodes is functional.'),(12,'one to one with load','There are two networks inter-connected. Each node of each network is inter-connected with exactly one node in the other network. If a node fails the corresponding part also fails. The number of nodes in each network is the same. This model in particular manages loads of some sort. Each component has a capacity defined either by characteristics of it or of the entity being modeled.'),(13,'state-interdependent network','In this kind of model there are no explicit links between layers. On each layer there\'s a standard network with nodes and links. Each nodes is in some \'state\'. Nodes with the same label in different layers share the same state, if the state of a node changes in some layer then it changes in every layer. Here each layer have the same amount of nodes. This model may be used to study contagion processes by defining a contagion matrix for each layer.'),(14,'PG-SCADA','There is a Power Grid network and a SCADA network (Supervisory Control And Data Acquisition). The PG network has root nodes that model a substation that provides power electricity through the power line network. The SCADA nodes represents either a router for communication line or a slave station that is equipped with a sensor (router node, sensor node). A sensor node is attached to every router node. The root node for SCADA models a server computer that monitors the system. Every node has exactly one inter-link (dependency link) with bidirectional dependency. The PG provides power to the SCADA and the PG is monitored by the SCADA. Intra net intercations are directed. If a PG link fails the subnet can\'t have energy. If a SCADA link fails the subnet can\'t be observed. If a sensor node fails it can\'t observe or control. A router fails if its PG node is not working.'),(15,'NON connectivity-dependency links','(Network of Networks) this model may contain N networks. These networks can be coupled by dependency links and connectivity links. A fraction q_ji is connected through dependency links. If q=1 then the networks are fully dependent. The connectivity links are the usual links that can connect a node to the largest connected component. A node is functional if its connected to some giant component (even in another network). This model may or not have feedback conditon, the no-feedback condition means that the dependency of 2 nodes is bidirectional (aj -> bi y bi -> ah => ah=aj). '),(16,'unidirectional PG-SCADA','There is a Power Grid network and a SCADA network (Supervisory Control And Data Acquisition). The PG network may suffer cascading failures due to overload in links but it does not depend on the SCADA net. If a node in the SCADA net fails nothing happens. If a node in the PG net stops  working or produces less energy than the minimum requiered by its dependent SCADA node, that SCADA node fails. Interactions between networks are unidirectional. The SCADA network depends on the PG, not the other way around. No 2 SCADA nodes depend on the same PG node and each SCADA node depends on one PG node. The PG network works with loads and the loads are redistributed in case of failure. A SCADA node also fails if it is no longer connected to the largest connected component.'),(17,'multiple support-dependence','This model describe relations between networks where a node in one network depends on one or more nodes in the other network. This dependence is unidirectional. The dependent node must have at least one support node in order to function and must belong to the giant component of functional nodes in the network it belongs to.'),(18,'supply-chain','This model presents a physical-layer and a cyber-layer. The physical-layer is composed by vertices, edges, load constraints for links, initial load of nodes and load constraints for nodes (V,E,W,L,C). In this layer the links are directed since they represent the chain supplier, mannufacterer, distributor and costumer. In case of failure the load propagates through the directed connections. The node capacity is usually related with the cost. In the case of the cyber-layer the tuple (V,E,L,W,C) represents the node, undirected links, and the analogous of the physical-layer (in this casee data-loads and hubs are being modelled). The dependencies between the 2 networks are \'one to one\' and reciprocal.'),(19,'load transfer','Here there are 2 interconnected networks. Each have capacities, weights and loads (nodes/links). When a node fails, its load  is transferred to the rest of the network. The overload produced on the network (as a node failed its overall capacity is reduced) is tranferred to the other network and it continues until a steady state is reached. In this model each node is connected to exactly one node in the other network, the amount of possible connections is given by the network with the least number of nodes. (if both networks have the same number of nodes, then each node in each network has one interlink). All links are undirected.'),(20,'k-n with load','There are 2 networks Gp (power-grid) and Gc (communication network). In Gc there are 2 types of nodes information relays and control nodes. Control nodes monitor and operate nodes in Gp. Each control node takes care of n Gp nodes and each Gp node is watched by k control nodes. Nodes in Gp also provide energy to the nodes in Gc. The amount of nodes in Gc that a node in Gp takes care of is given bya a modified version of balls and bins that takes into account the capacity of the nodes in Gp. Gp has loads and capacity. If a node in Gp fails the load is tranferred to the rest of Gp uniformly to the neighbors of the removed node. An overloaded node fails. The inter-links are directed and named \'control-dependency links\' and Energy-dependency links.'),(21,'k-n','There are 2 networks Gp (power-grid) and Gc (communication network). In Gc there are 2 types of nodes information relays and control nodes. Control nodes monitor and operate nodes in Gp. Each control node takes care of n Gp nodes and each Gp node is watched by k control nodes. Nodes in Gp also provide energy to the nodes in Gc. The amount of nodes in Gc that a node in Gp takes care of is given by a balls and bins.'),(22,'IP/MPLS over WDM','This model considers a standar telecommunications network. Here the WDM or optical network is composed by routers and their routing. IP/MPLS layer requires this network to communicate. If a router fails the dependent node in the other networks gets rerouted. If there is no re-routing possible it also fails. Interaction are bidirectional inside each network and unidirectional (Ip depends on optical) inter network.'),(23,'immediate load transfer','There are 2 interconnected networks. The nodes have loads and capacities. Neworks are inter-connected through interconnected links thar allow load transfer. If a node fail the load of each node is recalculated, if a node is overloaded then it is removed. This process continues until the system is stable. A node is considered functional if it belongs to the largest connected component. When recalculating the loads nodes in both networks are considered (immediate load transfer inter-network).'),(24,'at most one to one','There are two networks inter-connected. Each node of each network is inter-connected with at most one node in the other network. If a node fails the corresponding part also fails. The inter and intra interactions are bidirectional (non-directed). A node is considered functional if it belongs to the largest connected component.'),(25,'Inter-Dependent Markov Chain (IDMC) model','provides a probabilistic framework to capture the effects of interdependencies among physical networks on the stochastic dynamics of cascading failures in an abstract setting.'),(29,'overlay model with spine','There is a substrate network considered fixed (physical), a logical topology (logic) and on top of that there\'s the overlay network or overlay mapping. Overlay mapping is defined here as the process of mapping an application request to a substrate network whilst satisfying the specific requirements of the application.\r\n\r\n\"We consider a two layer network composed of the physical network on the bottom represented as GP with the set of nodes and links (VP , EP ), and on top the logical network GL represented by the set of logical nodes and links (VL , EL ). We assume that each logical node is connected to its corresponding physical node (i.e., VL = VP ).\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) the Spine concept, a subnetwork structure embedded at the physical layer with higher availability.\"\r\n\r\nThere are also loads and capacities of traffic.'),(30,'Cyber-Physical Power System','There\'s the cyber layer and a physical layer from the power system.  The physical layer is the power grid, it is undirected and have weights (loads) W. The elements of W are the electrical distances between two ends of the edges and equal to the reciprocal of the reactance of the corresponding edges, w = x−1 , where i and j ij ij are the two ends of the edge . The cyber layer represents the control network and is an unidrected graph. Interactions inter-network are directed. To be functional a node must \'receive\' (in-degree) at least one link and belong to the largest connected component. When a node is disconnected from the physical layer some links may fail due to overload and the network must verify if their power needs are satisfied.'),(31,'multiplex model','Multiplex network have nodes that appear in 2 or more layers but are \"the same\". Delete a multiplex node removes al layers while deleting a layer does not affect the other layers of the node. The giant component naturally consists of a set of connected multiplex nodes. A pair of multiplex nodes are regarded to have connection if there exists at least one type of link between them. Therefore, attacking some layer nodes may not destroy their connection with other nodes, and the set of nodes that remains at the end of damage is the mutually connected giant component.  '),(32,'innerdependency/interdependency links','Each node can have a dependency link and use it to connect itself with a node on its own network or on the other network. There are also non-directed without interaction links for the inner network connection. The dependency link means that the two nodes connected by it depend on each other, one of which fails, the other will fail too. Specifically, a fraction β of the dependency links are set as the inter-dependency links, others are the inner-dependency links. For inter-dependency links, the two stubs (nodes) are chosen randomly in the two net- works, respectively, and in the same networks for inner-dependency links. When β → 0, there is no dependency between the two networks and the model will reduce to the model of the single network with dependency link density q = 1 in ref. 28. When β → 1, our model will reduce to the original model of interdependent network proposed in ref4 (Buldyrev one to one).'),(33,'probabilistic one to one','If a node fails its dependent neighbour will lose their connectivity links with a certain probability (1-a). If it loses all its connectivity links always (a=1) then this model is exactly one to one. '),(34,'Spatial one to one with lifetime','The interactions between networks are the same as in the one to one model (bidirectional dependence). Inside the network links are non directed too. In this model not all the nodes of a network are necessarily connected. There is a \'distance\' between nodes given by the \'length\' of the link. This length exist thanks to the spatial embedding of the network (nodes have spatial coordinates). Two nodes acan get inter-connected (1 node in net. A 1 node in net. B) only if they are at a distance of at most r. If r=0 then the case is that of a single network and if r=inf then the interconnections aare simply usual connections at random. If a node does not belong to the giant component of the network, it fails. The components have a \'lifetime\' after which they begin to fail. The overall interdependent network also has a lifetime.');
