INSERT INTO `cat5` VALUES (1,'avalanche','Measures the amount of nodes lost after a cascading failure. This measure may be after one cascading failure as well as the averacge of the cascading failures that produces the removal of some or all nodes.'),(2,'capacity/load','Studies the effect that has the way the capacities or loads  are set on a network on some other network parameter.'),(3,'cascading time','Studies how long are the cascading failure that occur when the network confront some kind of failure. '),(4,'contagion','Studies the effect of different contagion behaviours on one or more layers and how they interact.'),(5,'cost','Studies the cost of adding or extracting elements on the network for some purpose (robustness, delay, etc.). They might be plain cost studies or cost efficiency studies (gain vs cost).'),(6,'coupling','Studies the effect on the interconnected network of different types of coupling. For this there must be more than random coupling criteria.'),(7,'delay','The delay of the information transmition through the network is studied.'),(8,'efficient path','Studies the variations of the length of some or all shortest paths in a network under some condition.'),(9,'genetic algorithm','A genetic algorithm is used to study the interdependent networks'),(10,'laplacian','Uses laplacian to study the behaviour of the network. It migh be information derived from the  laplacian, modified versions of it, etc.'),(11,'length','Studies the effect of changing some spacial parameter(length) on the measurments being taken of the network.'),(12,'lifetime','This may refer to components of the network having a lifetime and/or the network itself. Here the length and effects of these lifetimes are studied.'),(13,'Markov’s chain model','Studies the behaviour of the network under some condition using markov\'s chain models to predict it.'),(14,'optimization','Study how much of some value/characteristic must be/change in order to maximize or minimize some measurement.'),(15,'percolation','The percolation threshold is studied in order to get an insight about the robustness of the network. The percolation threshold is typically denoted by p_c and where p_c represent the critical value of p. In this context 1-p represents the probability of a node of failing or get disconnected. Thus, p_c is the point where no giant component remains (mayor failure of the network). The smaller the value of p_c the more robust is the network (this implies a bigger 1-p_c value and therefore that is necessary to disconnect more nodes to destry the network). When studying percolation phase transitions can be identified, these may be first or second order phase transitions. Second-order phase transitions are charecteristic of single networks, they decay continously when nodes are remodev. First-order phase transitions represent networks where an abrupt decay occurs at some point p_c. They usually happen on interdependent networks.'),(16,'percolation attacks','Nodes are removed at random with the probability given by the percolation studies. This kind of studies measures the impact of node removal through percolation. This kind of attack is always associated with percolation studies, although they may be considered as a kind of random attack too.'),(17,'random attack','Random elements of the network are removed. These elements are usually nodes but edges may be removed depending on the particular case. Some metric is used to measure the impact of the attacks. The elements may be removed all at once or one by one.'),(18,'recovery','A recovery process or strategy is studied. Recovery is when, from a fragmented/failure state a network starts to recover nodes to be able to work again. When coupled networks recover the recovery may trigger cascading failures, in those cases the network ends up maintaining its failed status.'),(19,'single net. comparison','Studies the difference between the single network version and the coupled network version on some aspect.'),(20,'size of giant component','Measures the size of the largest connected component. This may be measured at different points on the network \'history\' throughout the study.'),(21,'small cluster','Study the size/amount of small operating clusters a network may have A small operating cluster is a subgraph that has everything to be functional (for example the necessary interlinks) but is not connected to the largest connected component in its original network.'),(22,'stability','In the case of spacially embedded network they can be stable if they tolerate a radius targeted attack of any radius, meta stable if they\'re stable under attack of at most a r_c critical radius (a bigger radius makes it collapse) and unstable if under any radius the networks collapse.'),(23,'targeted attacks','Elements of the network are removed by some criteria. This criteria may be by some metric value, ranking, numeration, etc. These elements are usually nodes but edges may be removed depending on the particular case. Some metric is used to measure the impact of the attacks. The elements may be removed all at once or one by one.'),(24,'Probability of stop cascading failure','The probability of transiting from a state with some number of failures in a \"cascading failure state\" to a \"stable state\" with the same amount of failures.'),(25,'PMF of the failure size','PMF: the probability mass function. Studies the effect of some component on the probability mass function of the failure size.'),(26,'components','studies the amount of components'),(27,'Failure distribution','Studies the probability distribution of failures on edges and/or nodes. This failures may be classified or not (ex. load failure, attack failure, etc.)'),(28,'Probability of failure','studies the effect on some parameter of the probability of failure of their components'),(29,'Information for attack','Studies the effect of different parameters related with the \"amount of information\" that an attacker may have to attack a system.');
