INSERT INTO `metric` VALUES (1,'adjustment ratio','The adjustment ratio is defined by R=I1/I0 where I0 represents the initial investment on the network (which is the mean of the node weight/betweenness) and I1 is the mean of the minimum capacity needed for each node in order to resist cascading load failures due to the removal of one noe (it can be any node).','Invesment on the original nentwork, invesment to maintain the network functioning after the removal of one node.',3),(2,'Algebraic Connectivity derivative','The first derivative of the algebraic connectivity. The algebraic connectivity is the second smallest eigenvalue of the laplacian matrix of a graph. The authors of \"Abrupt transition in the structural formation of interconnected networks\" belive that the discontinuity point present in this derivative have correlation with the percolation threshold of the interdependent system.','The equation that gives the second smallest eigenvalue given the laplacian. ',4),(3,'amount of small funct. cluster','Amount of small functional clusters in the network (besides the largest connected component). The more clusters the more robust (they represent functional parts of the network). Small clusters are functional if they agree some conditions such as a minimum size and having the minimum requirements to function (have the necessary inter-links).','Amount of small functional clusters, size of the largest connected component, amount of isolated nodes.',1),(4,'Availability','How long a user can access to the services provided by the network','Time unnaccessible, total operating time.',9),(5,'Average GCC','Corresponds to the average size of the GCC on each network (initialy defined for 2 networks)','Average fractional size of each of the largest connected components in the system.',1),(6,'Avg. Norm S','Average normalized avalanche size. Avalanche is the amount of nodes lost after a cascading failure. In this metric each node is removed and then returned to the interdependent network. When a node is removed the avalanche size is measured. S corresponds to the average of these avalenche sizes.','Avalanche size after the removal of a node, for every node in the interdependent network.',1),(7,'Avg. S','Average avalanche size. Avalanche is the amount of nodes lost after a cascading failure. In this metric each node is removed and then returned to the interdependent network. When a node is removed the avalanche size is measured. S corresponds to the average of these avalenche sizes.','Avalanche size after the removal of a node, for every node in the interdependent network.',1),(8,'beta_c','beta at which the graph presents a phase transition. The capacity of an edge is a function of beta.','braking-point',2),(9,'beta_{c,s}','the smallest capacity threshold, if β < βc,s, the removal of any edge can lead to the cascading propagation in the whole interdependent networks.','',2),(10,'Characteristic valuation','It\'s also called fiedler vector and corresponds to the eigenvector associated to the second smallest eigenvalue of the laplacian matrix, the algebraic connectivity. This is studied in \"Abrupt transition in the structural formation of interconnected networks\" to understand the discontinuity point on the first derivative of the algebraic connectivity.','the laplacian. eigenvectors associated to the second smalles eigenvalue of the laplacian (algebraic connectivity)',4),(11,'Comprehensive efficiency index','It\'s an extension of the robustness index for 2 interdependent networks.','Number of nodes of each network, size of the larger connected components on each network.',1),(12,'Cost of protection','Measures the cost in money of adding redundance on a OTN (Optical Transport Network) to be robust against a dual failure.','leasing cost, length of the fibers, number of fibers.',3),(13,'critical attack radius','Radius of attack that makes the interdependent system collapse. Goes from 0 to infinite.','Attack radius, nodes left functional after the attack.',2),(14,'C_r','Cost of resilience. How much it cost to make a resilient overlay mapping.','know if a logical node is only used for backup in overlay mapping==1 and how many of them there are',3),(15,'density of infected nodes','Amount of nodes infected in relation to the total nodes after a lrge \'time\' t.','Amount of nodes infected. Total amount of nodes.',1),(16,'D_{avg}','Average delay of mapped overlay','Links to describe an overlay request, Set of logical links, Delay of a logical link',9),(17,'extended R-index','An extension of the usual R-index for interconnected networks.','The size of the largest connected component given the nodes that have failed.',1),(18,'f(A)','the relative size of the largest component of one network after failure compared to the total giant component at the moment (in this case the network is A)','Sizes of the networks',1),(19,'Failure extent','Number of nodes inactive after the cascading process','Number of nodes inactive after the cascading process',1),(20,'Failure speed','Failure extent per failure iteration. How abrupt is the cascading process.','Failure extent per failure iteration',8),(21,'G','Relative size of the largest connected component for 2 interdependent networks','Na\', Nb\' (sizes of the largest connected component after the attack) Na, Nb (original sizes) ',1),(22,'GCC','Or LCC, size of the largest/giant connected component.','Number of nodes on the largest connected component.',1),(23,'global efficiency','average efficiency where efficiency is measured as 1/d_{i,j}, i, j in nodes and d_{i,j} = length of the shortest path between i and j','N: number of nodes, d_{i,j} : shortest path between nodes i and j',5),(24,'Kirchoff index','A smaller Kirchoff index implies that, in general, more edges have to be removed to partition a graph into 2 connected sub-networks. This is calculated through Mthe Moore-Penrose pseudo- inverse of the graph Laplacians.','diagonal values  of the Moore-penrose pseudo inverse of the graph. Adjacency matrix and degree of each node is required',2),(25,'MTFR','Minimum total failure removals. Amount of nodes or edges (edge-MTFR, node-MTFR) to remove to cause total failure in the network (interdependent network).','Amount of nodes or edges to remove to cause total failure.',1),(26,'NOI','Number of Iterations or Cascade Lifetime. The amount of iterations that a cascading failure takes until it\'s done.',' Number of Iterations',1),(27,'O_{wb}','Percentage of overlay links','Links to describe an overlay request',1),(28,'p(s)','Given a Barabasi-Albert single network and an interdependen network (of 2 net), represents the proportion between the number of the increased failed nodes in the interdependent networks and the number of fauled nodes in the single BA network (for the same node removal)','amount of nodes failed in the inter networks and the single BA network.',1),(29,'p_c','Percolation threshold. Point where there\'s no longer a \'giant mutually connected component\'. All p < p_c, also \'destroy\' the network.','p of percolation, the size of the giant mutually connected component.',6),(30,'P_inf','Probability of existence of the giant mutually connected component, measures how likely is to have a giant mutually connected component given p such that 1-p is the probability of failure of a node.','p from percolation studies. The size N of the network.',6),(31,'p_inf(p)','Describe the size of the giant component (largest connected component) after the cascading failure ends, given p the probability othat a node doesn\'t fail (1-p is the amount of nodes removed in the actual measurement).','p the probability that a node doesn\'t fail',1),(32,'P∞','Average probability of a node of being connected to the largest connected cluster. P∞ = SUM 1/N * s_i. s_i es la probabilidad del nodo i de estar conectado al GCC. s_i depende de p la probabilidad de que un elemento se encuentre presente en la red (percolation).','The probability that node i is connected to the largets mutually connected component, Size of the networks (both nets are assumed to be of the same size).',7),(33,'q_c','Coupling strength that\'s critical and marks 2 different behavours (regarding p_c) for the same type of attack.','',2),(34,'ratio','Ratio of power line nodes that can still be observed and controled in spite of the failures','Working power line nodes that can still be observed after failures',1),(35,'Recovery robustness index','Similar to R-index. Given coupled network C and D, R_rc is the remainig functionality integrity of the coupled network after a fraction p of network c has been recovered.','Number of nodes, frc(p) is the remaining functionality integrity of the coupled network after the fraction of nodes p in network C has been recovered, p the fraction of nodes n network C that has been recovered (we have networks C and D).',1),(36,'Reliability','It\'s defined as R(t)=1 - lim(n(t)/S) S->inf, where n(t) is the number of system realizations that collapses at time t, and S is the total number of realizations. Conceptually it measures \"how close is the network to the criticality state (collapse)\".','number of system realizations that collapses at time t',2),(37,'Tc','Tolerance parameter threshold below which the interdependent network would suffer a cascading failure due to load redistribution. The tolerance parameters with some other parameters determines the capacity of a node.','',2),(38,'α0.5','The critical tolerance parameter α (Ci=(1+α)BCi(0), Ci: node i capacity) where G=0.5 after cascading failures.','Sizes of the networks, inicial betweenness centralities of each nodes, alfa, inicial sum of sizes of the networks',2),(39,'μp∞','or μc∞. the fractions of operating giant components in the final steady state.','nodes that remain functional',1);
