','not-in-selection',1996,'','','proceedings'),(205,'How to ‘Glue’ a Robust Smart-Grid?','ACM','a22-ranjan',2011,'Smart-grids are made up of two interdependent constituents: a power production and distribution network catering to a geographic area and a communication network that helps regulate and control the power-grid from which it derives its electricity. Thus, failures in one of the two networks can lead to failures in the other and in some cases cause a cascade or domino effect, bringing down the entire system completely. In this work, we present a theoretical frame- work to model and study the structural properties of such interdependent networks based on a topological interpreta- tion [4] of the Moore-Penrose pseudo-inverse of the graph Laplacians (L+). Using this framework, we study how the way in which node pairs in two networks are coupled or “glued” together (thereby introducing interdependence) af- fects the overall robustness of the resulting interdependent networks. Our study leads to some surprising (and some- what counter-intuitive) results.','Begins explaining the importance of the study of interdependent networks. It wants to show and study: 1.how can we characterize the robustness of interdependent network on a whole? 2.how is the overall robustness of two interdependent networks affected by the manner in which the two networks are coupled together? 3.How do we judicially select an appropriate collection of coupled node pairs to introduce interdependence so that the resulting interdependent networks are more robust to random failures or targeted attacks?. Then it explains the mathematic tools to be used on their framework: the moore-penrose pseudo inverse and the kirchoff index and the interpretation they give to them. Then they present the model used to handle interdependent networks and test their framework. They conclude that for high coupling rate the most robust network is obtained by coupling the least central nodes while for low coupling an interdependent network that couples the most central nodes is more robust.','proceedings'),(206,'Identification of influential spreaders in complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),(207,'Identification of k most vulnerable nodes in multi-layered network using a new model of interdependency','IEEE','not-in-selection',2014,'','','proceedings'),(208,'Identifying influential nodes in complex networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),(209,'Identifying, understanding, and analyzing critical infrastructure interdependencies','IEEE','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),(210,'ILOG CPLEX 12.0','ONLINE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','ONLINE'),(211,'Impact of service network topology on air transportation efficiency','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(212,'Impact of single links in competitive percolation','nature','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(213,'Improved El Ni{\\~n}o forecasting by cooperativity detection','NAS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(214,'Improving interdependent networks robustness by adding connectivity links','ScienceDirect','Improving-interdependent',2016,'Compared with a single and isolated network, interdependent networks have two types of links: connectivity link and dependency link. This paper aims to improve the robustness of interdependent networks by adding connectivity links. Firstly, interdependent networks failure model and four frequently used link addition strategies are briefly reviewed. Furthermore, by defining inter degree–degree difference, two novel link addition strategies are proposed. Finally, we verify the effectiveness of our proposed link addition strategies by comparing with the current link addition strategies in three different network models. The simulation results show that, given the number of added links, link allocation strategies have great effects on the robustness of interdependent networks, i.e., the double-network link allocation strategy is superior to single-network link allocation strategy. Link addition strategies proposed in this paper excel the current strategies, especially for BA interdependent networks. Moreover, our work can provide guidance on how to allocate limited resources to an existing interdependent networks system and optimize its topology to avoid the potential cascade failures.','This paper explores the idea of adding connectivity links between nodes that weren\'t previously connected to improve the robustness of the overall system. It is assumed a \"one to one\" model with 2 interdependent networks of the same size and topological structure. The robustness is measured through g =(Na\'+Nb\')/(Na+Nb) [Na\' = largest connected component after failure on network A, Na= original size of network A] the relative size of the largest connected component. The failures used to test the system robustness were random and the amount of nodes to remove from network A are given by a fraction p (There\'s also pc the critical p where the system collapses). In this paper 4 existing ways of adding connectivity links are used and 2 are proposed, 1.- random addition, 2.-Low degree: pair 2 nodes with the lowest degrees, 3.-Low betweenness: pair 2 nodes with the lowest betweenness, 4 .-Algebraic connectivity based: on each step you select a pair of nodes with the maximum absolute difference between elements of the field vector connect them. Then they define the Inter Degree-Degree difference (IDD) as IDDab(u,v) =  K^a_u -  K^b_v where K^a_u is the degree of u in network A. They also introduce the Average IDD as Sum^N_i=1 |IDDi|/N. With this they following 2 strategies for adding connectivity links are presented. 5.- Low IDD: given one of the participating networks (A or B) add a link between a pair of nodes with the minimum IDD (ideally negative) 6.-Random IDD: pair 2 random nodes on the same networks with IDD < 0. For the test they used Scale-Free, Erdos-Renyi and Small world networks. They also determined how many links would be added through fa = (M\')/(Ma+Mb) (here fa=M\'/4000).','journal'),(215,'Improving network robustness by edge modification','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(216,'Improving robustness of coupled networks against cascading failures','WorldScien.','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(217,'Improving the network robustness against cascading failures by adding links','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(218,'Inducing effect on the percolation transition in complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(219,'Infection dynamics on scale-free networks','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),(220,'Information cascades on degree-correlated random networks','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),(221,'Instability of scale-free networks under node-breaking avalanches','IOP','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),(222,'Inter-similarity between coupled networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(223,'Interacting epidemics on overlay networks','APS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),(224,'Interdependent networks with identical degrees of mutually dependent nodes','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(225,'Interdependent networks: reducing the coupling strength leads to a change from a first to second order percolation transition','APS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),(226,'Interdependent networks: vulnerability analysis and strategies to limit cascading failure','Springer','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(227,'Interdependent Spatially Embedded Networks: Dynamics at Percolation Threshold','IEEE','6727251',2013,'Spatially embedded systems of interdependent net- works with full dependency (q = 1) have been found to have a first-order percolation transition if the dependency link length (the maximum distance in lattice units between a node in one network and the node that it depends on in another network) is longer than a certain critical length rc ≈ 8. We find here that a similar result is valid for any finite value of q with a larger rc as q decreases. We also provide a theoretical approach which correctly predicts the relationship between rc and q. We also examine the dynamics at the percolation threshold pc for varying r and q and find that there are three different mechanisms of failure for every q depending on r. Below rc the system undergoes a continuous transition similar to standard percolation. Above rc there are two distinct first-order transitions for finite or infinite r, respectively.The transition for finite r is characterized by spreading of node failures through the system while the infinite r corresponds to a non-spatial cascading failure similar to the case of random networks. These results extend previous results on spatially embedded interdependent networks to the more realistic cases of partial dependency and shed new light on the specific dynamics of cascading failures in such systems.','This paper studies the relation between the degree of dependece on intercontected network and the maximum length of the interdependent links for the network to have a second order transition (after this maximum length the network will have a first order percolation transtion/ an abrupt transition). To do so lattices were used to model the phenomena. Given q : dependency level, r_c : maximum interdependent link lenght before first order percolation transition, r : dependency link length. They look at the behaviour of the giant component (largest connected component) near the percolation threshold for different r values (0<r<r_c, r>= r_c, r = inf) and find relationships between them. They find that interdependent networks can avoid spreading catastrophic cascades only if the distance between interdependent nodes is below rc, though increasing the distance to a value much greater than rc can also provide a small increase in robustness with respect to random attacks.','proceedings'),(228,'Introduction to percolation theory','CRC','not-in-selection',1994,'','','book'),(229,'Is multilayer networking feasible?','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),(230,'Jamming transition in air transportation networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),(231,'Knowledge diffusion in the collaboration hypernetwork','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(232,'Laplacian Eigenvectors of Graphs. Perron-Frobenius and Faber-Krahn Type Theorems,','Springer','not-in-selection',2007,'','','--'),(233,'Laplacian matrices of graphs: a survey','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1994,'','','journal'),(234,'Laplacian of graphs and algebraic connectivity','IMPAS','not-in-selection',1989,'','','journal'),(235,'Large scale structure and dynamics of complex networks: from information technology to finance and natural sciences','World Scien.','not-in-selection',2007,'','','book'),(236,'Layered complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),(237,'Layered percolation','arXiv','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(238,'Leaders in social networks, the delicious case','PLS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(239,'Linear algebra and its applications','Pearson','not-in-selection',2005,'','','misc'),(240,'Link overlap, viability, and mutual percolation in multiplex networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2015,'','','journal'),(241,'Local search and the local structure of NP-complete problems','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1992,'','','journal'),(242,'Localized attacks on spatially embedded networks with dependencies','nature','srep08934',2015,'Many real world complex systems such as critical infrastructure networks are embedded in space and their components may depend on one another to function. They are also susceptible to geographically localized damage caused by malicious attacks or natural disasters. Here, we study a general model of spatially embedded networks with dependencies under localized attacks. We develop a theoretical and numerical approach to describe and predict the effects of localized attacks on spatially embedded systems with dependencies. Surprisingly, we find that a localized attack can cause substantially more damage than an equivalent random attack. Furthermore, we find that for a broad range of parameters, systems which appear stable are in fact metastable.Though robust to random failures—even of finite fraction—if subjected to a localized attack larger than a critical size which is independent of the system size (i.e., a zero fraction), a cascading failure emerges which leads to complete system collapse.','This paper proposes an approach to describe and predict the effects of localized attacks on spatially embedded systems with dependencies. To do so 2D \'diluted\' lattices with edge length constraints are considered to represent interdimentional networks. It is found that there are 3 possible states : stable, metastable, unestable when under \"local attacks\". A local attack is one that is centered on a node and affects nodes (destroys them) on a specific radius. Interdependent lattices are stable if under any radius of attack  (infinite) they don\'t collapse, metastable if under a certain attack radius is stable but above that radius it collapses and unestable if even a zero radius attacks makes the networks collapse. This work presents a complete analytical and simulation results to identify the interdependent lattice state. The results are in great concordance with the expected results from the analitycal part. IIt showed that local attacks bounded to \'physical\' radius can be catastrophic in a wide range of cases (interconected networks) while on a single lattice the local attack might not have an effect at all. ','journal'),(243,'Managing disruption risks in supply chains','WOL','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(244,'Markov chains: Gibbs fields, Monte Carlo simulation, and queues','Springer','not-