ex networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(300,'Optimal intentional islanding to enhance the robustness of power grid networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(301,'Optimal path in random networks with disorder: A mini review','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(302,'Optimal weighting scheme and the role of coupling strength against load failures in degree-based weighted interdependent networks','ScienceDirect','Optimal-weighting',2013,'The optimal weighting scheme and the role of coupling strength against load failures on symmetrically and asymmetrically coupled interdependent networks were investigated. The degree-based weighting scheme was extended to interdependent networks, with the flow dynamics dominated by global redistribution based on weighted betweenness centrality. Through contingency analysis of one-node removal, we demonstrated that there still exists an optimal weighting parameter on interdependent networks, but it might shift as compared to the case in isolated networks because of the break of symmetry. And it will be easier for the symmetrically and asymmetrically coupled interdependent networks to achieve robustness and better cost configuration against the one-node-removal-induced cascade of load failures when coupling strength was weaker. Our findings might have great generality for characterizing load-failure-induced cascading dynamics in real-world degree-based weighted interdependent networks.','This paper studies de Global load-based redistribution by assigning the load through intra-degree and inter-degree properties. The robustness is measured by removing each node once and re-adjusting the capacities of the nodes to take the load of the one node removal without falling apart. Then the investment of the initial network is compared with the invesment of the adjusted network. With this the optimal weighting parameter (thetha*) is the one resulting in the minimum investment (I1*). They define the adjustment ratio R = I1/I0, the smaller the ratio, the easier it is for the network to gain robustness against one-node removal from the initial configuration. The tests are performed over Scale-Free and Erdos-Renyi networks with symetrical coupling [N=Na=Nb=100, <k>=<ka>=<kb>=4, <¨ka>=<¨kb>=<¨k>=2], and asymmetrical coupling [Na=50, Nb=100, <k>=<ka>=<kb>=6, <¨ka>=4,<¨kb>=2].','journal'),(303,'Optimal weighting scheme for suppressing cascades and traffic congestion in complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),(304,'Optimization of network robustness to random breakdowns','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),(305,'Optimization of network robustness to waves of targeted and random attacks','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(306,'Optimization of robustness and connectivity in complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),(307,'Optimization of robustness of complex networks','Springer','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),(308,'Optimization of robustness of scale-free network to random and targeted attacks','WorldScien.','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(309,'Optimizing algebraic connectivity by edge rewiring','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(310,'Optimizing complex networks for resilience against cascading failure','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),(311,'Optimizing network topology for cascade resilience','Springer','not-in-selection',2012,'','','collection'),(312,'Organization of modular networks','APS','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),(313,'Organizations of rich nodes in complex networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),(314,'Origins of fractality in the growth of complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),(315,'Path diversity improves the identification of influential spreaders','IOP','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(316,'Percolation and conduction','APS','not-in-selection',1973,'','','journal'),(317,'Percolation and epidemics in random clustered networks','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),(318,'Percolation in interdependent and interconnected networks: Abrupt change from second-to first-order transitions','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(319,'Percolation in multiplex networks with overlap','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(320,'Percolation in networks composed of connectivity and dependency links','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(321,'Percolation in networks of networks with random matching of nodes in different layers','arXiv','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(322,'Percolation in real interdependent networks','nature','nphys3374',2015,'The function of a real network depends not only on the reliability of its own components, but is affected also by the simultaneous operation of other real networks coupled with it. Whereas theoretical methods of direct applicability to real isolated networks exist, the frameworks developed so far in percolation theory for interdependent network layers are of little help in practical contexts, as they are suited only for special models in the limit of infinite size. Here, we introduce a set of heuristic equations that takes as inputs the adjacency matrices of the layers to draw the entire phase diagram for the interconnected network. We demonstrate that percolation transitions in interdependent networks can be understood by decomposing these systems into uncoupled graphs: the intersection among the layers, and the remainders of the layers. When the intersection dominates the remainders, an interconnected network undergoes a smooth percolation transition. Conversely, if the intersection is dominated by the contribution of the remainders, the transition becomes abrupt even in small networks. We provide examples of real systems that have developed interdependent networks sharing cores of ‘high quality’ edges to prevent catastrophic failures.','This paper proposes a method to satudy the percolation thresholds of complex coupled networks. It recognizes problems on the assumptions of previous model (the graph models topology is not specified by a one-zero adjacency matrix, they\'re applied to infinitely large systems) that real interconnected networks don\'t possess. Then a methodology to describe percolation transitions is explained. By defining several concepts and steps the paper arrives to an euristic equation for the probability that a node i is in the largest mutually connected cluster of the system. They determine that the percolation transition depends on size of the intersection of the graph vs the remainder. The method is tested by comparing empyrical results against the theoretical results obtained from the heuristic equation. One thing apreciated is that in heterogeneous graphs the nature of transition is not determined by the number of edges shared across the layers but their quality. The results of the theoretical and empyrical results are very similar concluding that the framework is able to help identify cores of quality links that can prevent catastrophic failures in real systems.','journal'),(323,'Percolation in self-similar networks','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(324,'Percolation of a general network of networks','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(325,'Percolation of interdependent networks with intersimilarity','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(326,'Percolation of localized attack on complex networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2015,'','','journal'),(327,'Percolation of partially interdependent networks under targeted attack','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),(328,'Percolation of partially interdependent scale-free networks','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(329,'Percolation on dense graph sequences','IMS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),(330,'Percolation on interacting net