virtual networks for resiliency and efficiency','IEEE','not-in-selection',2007,'','','proceedings'),(348,'Random Graphs','Springer','not-in-selection',1985,'','','journal'),(349,'Random graphs containing arbitrary distributions of subgraphs','APS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),(350,'Random graphs with arbitrary degree distributions and their applications','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),(351,'Random graphs with clustering','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),(352,'Random walks on complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),(353,'Reaction--diffusion processes and metapopulation models in heterogeneous networks','nature','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),(354,'Recent development on supply chain supernetwork modeling','Shanghai.LD','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(355,'Recovering from disruptions of interdependent critical infrastructures','-','not-in-selection',2001,'','','proceedings'),(356,'Recovery from malicious transactions','IEEE','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),(357,'Reflection on supernetwork','Shanghai.LD','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(358,'Reliability Analysis of Interdependent Networks Using Percolation Theory','IEEE','6727252',2013,'Many complex systems have functional interde- pendency between each other and can be modeled as interdepen- dent networks. The failure of a small fraction of nodes in inter- dependent networks may lead to catastrophic cascading failures across network borders. Starting from a model of static interde- pendent networks, by introducing lifetime for each component, we study the reliability properties and lifetimes of the interde- pendent networks to which these components belong. Depending on the lifetime of the network components, the trigger of cascad- ing failures will shape the interdependent networks reliability. In this framework, we analyze the evolution of the reliability prop- erties of interdependent networks, and compare them with single networks. Interdependent SF networks are found to have lower reliability than interdependent ER networks.','The main objective of this work is to study the reliabilty of a network and its overall \'lifetime\' given that each component have its own lifetime after which the components begin to fail an collapse. They use the one to one model of dependency and for simplicity they couple networks that have the same amount of nodes. With the lifetime and reliability studies \'size of the largest connected component\' are also analyzed. Comparisons between single networks and interconnected networks with components with lifetime are performed. Overall lifetime versus average component lifetime and standar deviation lifetime as well as degradation or reliability over time are performed. It is found that the lifetime of interconnected networks is significantly shorter than the lifetime of single networks under the same conditions, SF (scale-free) networks presents an inferior reliability versus ER (erdos-renyi) networks and that due the combined effect of structure and time the network lifetime decreases with standard deviation of component life distribution, while the lifetime of the single network increases with the standard deviation of the component life distribution.','proceedings'),(359,'Reliability engineering','JohnWiley&Sons','not-in-selection',2012,'','','book'),(360,'Renormalization group analysis of the small-world network model','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1999,'','','journal'),(361,'Resilience in multilayer networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',1999,'','','journal'),(362,'Resilience of complex networks to random breakdown','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(363,'Resilience of the internet to random breakdowns','APS','not-in-selection',2000,'','','journal'),(364,'Resilient multilayer traffic engineering through dynamic path restoration','Citeseer','not-in-selection',2004,'','','proceedings'),(365,'Resilient overlay networks','ACM','not-in-selection',2001,'','','proceedings'),(366,'Revealing the process of edge-based-attack cascading failures','Springer','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),(367,'Review on modeling and simulation of interdependent critical infrastructure systems','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(368,'Robust allocation of weighted dependency links in cyber–physical networks','ScienceDirect','Robust-allocation',2015,'Interdependent network models are often used to show how one network has an effect on another network through dependencies. In this paper, we propose a novel interdependent network model which consists of two individual networks with unequal numbers of nodes and one-to-multiple weighted dependency links between the two networks. Based on realistic assumptions, this model differs from previous works that considered equal numbers of nodes in the two networks and identical dependency links. We formulate an optimization problem to allocate dependency links using least resources. This novel model enhances the practicability of traditional cyber–physical system structures, but it makes the dependency link deployment problem more complex and the optimization problem cannot be solved in large networks. To overcome this problem, we propose a new algorithm based on a revised network flow method. Extensive simulations on random networks and real networks show that our deployment method produces topologies that are more robust than the ones obtained by other deployment techniques. Results indicate that our algorithm is efficient and cost-effective in designing robust interdependent networks, and our deployment method is suitable for networks of any size.','This paper tackles the problem of allocating links (dependency links that connect 2 different networks in particular) given that each one have a cost and there\'s a budget (a limit to the amount of link you can afford). Here, as in other papers, the biggest connected component is the one that\'s considered functional. However they propose a one-to-multiple dependence over networks that are no neccesarily the same one or have the same amount of nodes (Although for simulation pourposes they couple networks with the same \"structure\"). For a node to properly function it has to be connected to the largest connected component and have at least one dependency link. The robustness metric they use is the average value of the size of the largest connected component divided by the original size of the network for each network. The allocation process is divided on 2 steps. The first one is Basic connectivity to ensure that every node has at least one dependency link (you need max(Na,Nb) links). The second step is the augmented connectivity, here the remaining budget is use according to some strategy. The authors say that \"the aim of augmented connectivity is to achieve minimum variance of node degree\" (for better robustness). To perform the tests they use 2 strategies \"maximize the number of dependencies\" and \"random\" on ER networks coupled (they did not use the same network, they have differen sizes Nb=(1+a)Na).','journal'),(369,'Robust-yet-fragile nature of interdependent networks','APS','not-in-selection',2015,'','','journal'),(370,'Robustness analysis of static routing on networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(371,'Robustness envelopes of networks','Oxford Un.','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(372,'Robustness in simple biochemical networks','nature','not-in-selection',1997,'','','journal'),(373,'Robustness measure for power grids with respect to cascading failures','ITC','not-in-selection',2011,'','','proceedings'),(374,'Robustness of a network formed by n interdependent networks with a one-to-one correspondence of dependent nodes','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),(375,'Robustness of a network of networks','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(376,'Robustness of a partially interdependent network formed of clustered networks','APS','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(377,'Robustness of complex networks with the local protection strategy against cascading failures','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(378,'Robustness of interdependent and interconnected clustered networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(379,'Robustness of interdependent networks under several intentional attack strategies','Shanghai.LD','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),(380,'Robustness of interdependent networks under targeted attack','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(381,'Robustness of Interdependent Networks: The case of communication networks and the power grid','IEEE','6831395',2013,'We study the robustness of interdependent networks, in which the state of one network depends on the state of the other network and vice versa. In particular, we focus on the interdependency between the power grid and communication networks, where the grid depends on communications for its control, and the communication network depends on the grid for power. A real-world example is the Italian blackout of 2003, when a small failure in the power grid cascaded between the two networks and led to a massive blackout. In this paper, we study the minimum number of node failures needed to cause total blackout (i.e., all nodes in both networks to fail).In the case of unidirectional interdependency between the networks we show that the problem is NP-hard, and develop heuristics to find a near-optimal solution. On the other hand, we show that in the case of bidirectional interdependency this problem can be solved in polynomial time. We believe that this new interdependency model gives rise to important, yet unexplored, robust network design problems for interdependent networked infrastructures.','In this paper the authors analyze the robustness of interdependent networks where the interdependencies are manifested 2 ways. For each way they want to know the minimum number of node failures needed to cause total blackout. They focus on the example of SCADA-Power grid dependencies. The first case considered is the unidirectional dependency case where if a router node depends on a certain power node it doesn\'t mean that power node depends on that router node. The second case is the one to one dependency where if one of the coupled nodes fails the other fails as well. The former case is proven to be an NP-complete problem so heuristics to tackle it are given, while the latter case is a polynomial problem. The tests are performed over star like networks to measure the effects of the interdependencies on the cascading failures and those effects only (star like means that, for ex., on the power grid every node is connected to the generator and generators can function by themselves). With this last assumption the coupled networks can be seen as bipartite graphs. They found that the network of Italy is robust to total failure. However, they showed that parts of the network are very vulnerable to failures. The robustness metric used is the minimun number of nodes that must be removed for total collapse.','proceedings'),(382,'Robustness of multilayer oscillator networks','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(383,'Robustness of n interdependent networks with partial support-dependence relationship','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(384,'Robustness of network of networks under targeted attack','APS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(385,'Robustness of the European power grids under intentional attack','APS','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),(386,'Robustness of the western United States power grid under edge attack strategies due to cascading failures','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(387,'Role of optical network and spare router strategy in resilient IP backbone architecture','IEEE','not-in-selection',2003,'','','proceedings'),(388,'Roles of mixing patterns in cooperation on a scale-free networked game','APS','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),(389,'Router security configuration guide, version 1.1 b','TechRep SNAC NSA','not-in-selection',2003,'','','techreport'),(390,'Routing in scale-free networks based on expanding betweenness centrality','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(391,'Rules for biologically inspired adaptive network design','AAAS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),(392,'Sandpile cascades on interacting tree-like networks','arXiv','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),(393,'Scale-free networks: a decade and beyond','AAAS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),(394,'Scale-free user-network approach to telephone network traffic analysis','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(395,'Scaling approach to anisotropic magnetic systems statics','Springer','not-in-selection',1969,'','','journal'),(396,'Scaling approach to tricritical phase transitions','APS','not-in-selection',1972,'','','journal'),(397,'Scientific collaboration networks. II. Shortest paths, weighted networks, and centrality','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),(398,'Searching for superspreaders of information in real-world social media','nature','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(399,'Self-avoiding walks on random networks of resistors and diodes','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1987,'','','journal'),(400,'Self-organized similarity, the evolutionary emergence of groups of similar species','NAS','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),(401,'Self-similarity of complex networks','nature','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(402,'Service overlay networks: SLAs, QoS, and bandwidth provisioning','IEEE','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),(403,'Shared backup router resources: realizing virtualized network resilience','IEEE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(404,'Small Cluster in Cyber Physical Systems: Network Topology, Interdependence and Cascading Failures','IEEE','6863675',2015,'In cyber physical system (CPS), computational resources and physical resources are strongly correlated and mutually dependent. Cascading failures occur between coupled networks, cause the system more fragile than single network. Besides widely used metric giant component, we study small cluster (small component) in interdependent networks after cascading failures occur. We first introduce an overview on how small clusters distribute in various single networks. Then we propose a percolation theory based mathematical method to study how small clusters be affected by the interdependence between two coupled networks. We prove that the upper bounds exist for both the fraction and the number of operating small clusters. Without loss of generality, we apply both synthetic network and real network data in simulation to study small clusters under different interdependence models and network topologies. The extensive simulations highlight our findings: except the giant component, considerable proportion of small clusters exists, with the remaining part fragmenting to very tiny pieces or even massive isolated single vertex; no matter how the two networks are tightly coupled, an upper bound exists for the size of small clusters. We also discover that the interdependent small-world networks generally have the highest fractions of operating small clusters. Three attack strategies are compared: Inter Degree Priority Attack, Intra Degree Priority Attack and Random Attack. We observe that the fraction of functioning small clusters keeps stable and is independent from the attack strategies.','Here a different view on the robustness measurements is shown. The authors say that measuring the largest connected component and assuming that a node that\'s not connected to it is non operational is wrong. Instead they propose to take into account the amount of small clusters that remain functional after an attack. A node remains operational if it is connected to a cluster with a minimum size delta and it is interconnected. They also propose an alternative to the one to one coupling that they call \"k-n\", in this coupling they have unidirectional links and two types of nodes (one connects with k other nodes, the other with n). They show that the semaller the delta the more robust is the network. And that it is necessary to take small clusters (that are functional) into account in order to properly evaluate network robustness.','journal'),(405,'Small worlds: the dynamics of networks between order and randomness','PUP','not-in-selection',1999,'','','book'),(406,'Smart grid communications and networking','CUP','not-in-selection',2012,'','','book'),(407,'Spatial networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(408,'Spatially localized attacks on interdependent networks: the existence of a finite critical attack size','arXiv','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(409,'Spectra of random graphs with given expected degrees','NAS','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),(410,'Spectral graph theory','AMS','not-in-selection',1997,'','','book'),(411,'Spectral measure of structural robustness in complex networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(412,'Spectral redemption in clustering sparse networks','NAS','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(413,'Spin glass theory and beyond.','WSP','not-in-selection',1990,'','','journal'),(414,'Spontaneous recovery in dynamical networks','nature','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(415,'Spread of epidemic disease on networks','APS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),(416,'Spreading dynamics in complex networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(417,'Spreading of cooperative behaviour across interdependent groups','nature','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(418,'Stability and topology of scale-free networks under attack and defense strategies','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(419,'Statistical mechanics of complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),(420,'Statistical physics of social dynamics','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),(421,'Structural vulnerability of power systems: A topological approach','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(422,'Structural vulnerability of the North American power grid','APS','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),(423,'Structure of shells in complex networks','APS','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),(424,'Study of the Use of a Genetic Algorithm to Improve Networked System-of-Systems Resilience','ScienceDirect','Study-of-the-use',2014,'Large scale failures or degradation resulting from smaller initial failures or disruptions in networked system-of- systems are an issue in multiple areas - for example cascading failures in electrical power grids or large disruptions in national air traffic due to local or regional weather conditions. The system architecture can have a significant impact on system-of-systems susceptibility to large scale failures. /The study presented in this paper uses a simple interdependent networked system-of-systems failure model, integrated into a unique objective function that addresses both the overall level of failure and the rate of failure progression, and a genetic algorithm to demonstrate an integrated failure modeling based optimization method to select system-of-systems architectures for improved resiliency. /The results for the integrated failure model/genetic algorithm model results converged rapidly to a steady state values. This initial integration shows a possible path forward to more sophisticated model integration and optimization and demonstrates a basic level of feasibility for this general approach.','This paper proposes a genetic algorithm to optimize the robustness of networks against failures. The model is based on 2 interdependent grid type networks of dimension Xi x Yi and Xj x Yj. For the experiments each network has 2500 nodes. The interactions between the networks are unidirectional, that is, the failure propagates to the other network only if in the original network fails a node such that a node in the other network depended on it.  For the algorithm attacks are used, these attacks strike an area of the network defined by a radius and center. The nodes that fail become \"inactive\". This paper measures the extent of the fully developed failure region and the speed of the cascading process to measure the robustness of the network. Here interdependence intra-network are not taken into consideration. Attacks were performed at random.','journal'),(425,'Stuxnet under the microscope','ESET LLC','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),(426,'Successful strategies for competing networks','nature','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(427,'Sudden emergence of a giantk-core in a random graph','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1996,'','','journal'),(428,'Supercooled and glassy water','IOP','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),(429,'Supply chain supernetworks and environmental criteria','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),(430,'Suppressing cascades of load in interdependent networks','NAS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),(431,'Survivability of multiple fiber duct failures','researchgate','not-in-selection',2001,'','','proceedings'),(432,'Survivable IP/MPLS-over-WSON multilayer network optimization','OSA','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(433,'Survivable paths in multilayer networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2012,'','','proceedings'),(434,'Survivable routing of mesh topologies in IP-over-WDM networks by recursive graph contraction','IEEE','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),(435,'Sustainable fashion supply chain management under oligopolistic competition and brand differentiation','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),(436,'Synchronization in interdependent networks','AIP','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(437,'Temporal networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),(438,'The anatomy of a large-scale hypertextual web search engine','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',1998,'','','journal'),(439,'The art of computer programming, volume 2','Addison-Wesley','not-in-selection',1997,'','','book'),(440,'The art of computer programming: sorting and searching','Pearson','not-in-selection',1998,'','','book'),(441,'The combined effect of connectivity and dependency links on percolation of networks','Springer','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(442,'The effect of attack cost on network robustness','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(443,'The effect of clustering-based and degree-based weighting on robustness in symmetrically coupled heterogeneous interdependent networks','IEEE','6722433',2013,'We studied robustness of symmetrically coupled interdependent networks against load failures when the flow dynamics is dominated by global redistribution based on weighted betweenness centrality. Three kinds of weighting schemes, which are random, clustering-based, and degree-based, respectively, were compared. We demonstrated that both the clustering-based and degree-based weighting scheme outweigh random weighting on robustness against the cascade of load failures in the symmet- rically coupled interdependent networks. In a limited range of weighting parameters, degree-based weighting scheme outweigh clustering-based scheme. Outside of that range, clustering-based weighting scheme outweigh degree-based scheme. And it will be easier for the symmetrically coupled interdependent network to achieve robustness against one-node removal and better cost configuration against the cascade of load failures when relative interconnection intensity was weaker under degree-based and clustering-based weighting schemes. Our findings might have great generality for characterizing load-failure-induced cascading dynamics in real-world weighted interdependent networks.','The paper is centered on the proposal and testing of different ways of assigning weight to links on interdependent networks. This weights are used to determine how to redistribute the load of the network in case that occurs a node failure. This last point is important to avoid further cascading failures (intra and inter networks) due to excesive load. In this paper the weighting idea is extended to interconnected networks, the weighting strategies are extended as well (betweennes, degree, clustering). Here the cost of the weighting is also studied. A network would be considered \"more robust\" if for it is \'easier\' to gain robustness (cost wise).','proceedings'),(444,'The effect of interdependence on the percolation of interdependent networks','ScienceDirect','The-effect-of',2014,'Two stochastic models are proposed to generate a system composed of two interdependent scale-free (SF) or ErdÆs–Rényi (ER) networks where interdependent nodes are connected with an exponential or power-law relation, as well as different dependence strength, respectively. Each subnetwork grows through the addition of new nodes with constant accelerating random attachment in the first model but with preferential attachment in the second model. The two subnetworks interact with multi-support and undirectional dependence links. The effects of dependence relations and strength between subnetworks are analyzed in the percolation behavior of fully interdependent networks against random failure, both theoretically and numerically, and as a result, for both relations: interdependent SF networks show a second-order percolation phase transition and the increased dependence strength decreases the robustness of the system, whereas, interdependent ER networks show the opposite results. In addition, the power-law relation between networks yields greater robustness than the exponential one at the given dependence strength.','In this paper they present a simple framework but with 2 different models possible. To resume: once the network is modeled they test the resilience by measuring the percolation threshold for each initial p. The models are constructed on steps where nodes and links are added. There are two types of links: connectivity links (intra) and dependency links (inter). The first model begins with m0 nodes and n0 connectivity links on each network (A and B), on each step t it add a node to every network. Each node in A adds mA links, it attaches itself with a 1-qa fraction of nodes in the same network through connectivity links. The rest of the links are dependency links who are attached to nodes in B. (For each node in B is the same). The second model is initiated in the same way but when the nodes are added on each network and on each step t the link addition it\'s done by the constant acceleration scenario. Given the new node in A, this scenario adds a connectivity link between 2 nodes in A with probability s, it must be satisfied that the expected amount of links is st. In the case of the addition of dependency links they can be added at random or preferentially (DL) (exponenctial dependence-degree dist or power-law-degree dist.).  This second model ends up creating a ER network with poisson degree distribution. The tests performed study the percolation threshold pc for different q (level of dependence), and the sizes of the largest connected components depending on p (the cascading process begins by removing 1-p nodes from network A). A node is considered functional if it belongs to the largest connected component and has at leats 1 dependency link. With the tests theoretycal predictions were shown and both test results and prediction results were contrasted.','journal'),(445,'The evolution of random graphs','','not-in-selection',1960,'','','journal'),(446,'The extreme vulnerability of interdependent spatially embedded networks','nature','nphys2727',2013,'Recent studies show that in interdependent networks a very small failure in one network may lead to catastrophic consequences. Above a critical fraction of interdependent nodes, even a single node failure can invoke cascading failures that may abruptly fragment the system, whereas below this critical dependency a failure of a few nodes leads only to a small amount of damage to the system. So far, research has focused on interdependent random networks without space limitations. However, many real systems, such as power grids and the Internet, are not random but are spatially embedded. Here we analytically and numerically study the stability of interdependent spatially embedded networks modelled as lattice networks. Surprisingly, we find that in lattice systems, in contrast to non-embedded systems, there is no critical dependency and any small fraction of interdependent nodes leads to an abrupt collapse. We show that this extreme vulnerability of very weakly coupled lattices is a consequence of the critical exponent describing the percolation transition of a single lattice.','The paper begins explaining that not all networks are random and that in many cases these are spatially embedded. In order to study the effects of this kind of structure they use percolation theory and lattice graphs, though they acknowlodge that most of these networks are not lattices. In this paper they show the theory using interdependent networks composed by two networks. It is focused on the case where both networks have the same degree distribution. With this they proceed to analyze the size of the giant component at criticality in function of the coupling strenght q, for this, they used different simulated and real networks coupled together. It concludes that for spatially embedded networks even a weak coupling lead to a relatively large-scale collapse while for random networks the discontinuity size does not have a singular point. In the case of lattice-RR (Random Regular) the singularity is slightly weaker than the lattice-lattice case.','journal'),(447,'The fractal nature of a diffusion front and the relation to percolation','LesEditionsP','not-in-selection',1985,'','','journal'),(448,'The igraph software package for complex network research','InterJournal','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),(449,'The impact of supply chain integration on the “snowball effect” in the transmission of disruptions: An empirical evaluation of the model','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(450,'The impact of the topology on cascading failures in a power grid model','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(451,'The interaction between multiplex community networks','AIP','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(452,'The power grid as a complex network: a survey','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(453,'The resilience of WDM networks to probabilistic geographical failures','IEEE','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(454,'The resilient enterprise: overcoming vulnerability for competitive advantage','MITPress','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(455,'The robustness and restoration of a network of ecological networks','AAAS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),(456,'The robustness of interdependent clustered networks','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(457,'The robustness of interdependent transportation networks under targeted attack','IOP','not-in-selection',2013,'','','39'),(458,'The role of the airline transportation network in the prediction and predictability of global epidemics','NAS','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),(459,'The severity of supply chain disruptions: design characteristics and mitigation capabilities','WOL','not-in-selection',2007,'','','journal'),(460,'The structure and dynamics of multilayer networks','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(461,'The Structure and Dynamics of Networks','PUP','not-in-selection',2006,'','','journal'),(462,'The structure and function of complex networks','SIAM','not-in-selection',2003,'','','journal'),(463,'The topological and electrical structure of power grids','IEEE','not-in-selection',2010,'','','proceedings'),(464,'The unreasonable effectiveness of tree-based theory for networks with clustering','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(465,'The worldwide air transportation network: Anomalous centrality, community structure, and cities\' global roles','NAS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','journal'),(466,'Theoretical approaches to node assignment','Uni.Cargn','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),(467,'Tight lower bound for percolation threshold on an infinite graph','APS','not-in-selection',2014,'','','journal'),(468,'Tolerance of scale-free networks against attack-induced cascades','APS','not-in-selection',2005,'','','451'),(469,'Toward self-healing energy infrastructure systems','IEEE','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),(470,'Towards design principles for optimal transport networks','APS','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),(471,'Towards designing robust coupled networks','nature','srep01969',2013,'Natural and technological interdependent systems have been shown to be highly vulnerable due to cascading failures and an abrupt collapse of global connectivity under initial failure. Mitigating the risk by partial disconnection endangers their functionality. Here we propose a systematic strategy of selecting a minimum number of autonomous nodes that guarantee a smooth transition in robustness. Our method which is based on betweenness is tested on various examples including the famous 2003 electrical blackout of Italy. We show that, with this strategy, the necessary number of autonomous nodes can be reduced by a factor of five compared to a random choice. We also find that the transition to abrupt collapse follows tricritical scaling characterized by a set of exponents which is independent on the protection strategy.','This paper focuses on the problem of decoupling nodes in order to make a more robust network. A methodology to choose specific nodes by a certain criteria, in this case centrality measures, is presented. The robustness of the coupled networks is studied through an extension of the R-index for more than one layer. It\'s demonstrated that by decoupling nodes by the criteria is possible to change the percolation transition from a discontinuous (catastrophic) to a smooth one. Also by using certain critera instead of choosing random it is possible to reduce the amount of nodes to decouple in order to make the networks more robust.  ','journal'),(472,'Transient dynamics increasing network vulnerability to cascading failures','APS','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),(473,'Transport in networks with multiple sources and sinks','IOP','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),(474,'Transport on coupled spatial networks','APS','not-in-selection',2012,'','','journal'),(475,'Tricritical exponents and scaling fields','APS','not-in-selection',1972,'','','journal'),(476,'Tricritical point in explosive percolation','APS','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(477,'Uber quadratische Formen mit reellen Koeffizienten','Springer','not-in-selection',1905,'','','journal'),(478,'Uberber die Eigenwerte bei den Differentialgleichungen der mathematischen Physik','Springer','not-in-selection',1920,'','','journal'),(479,'Ultra high capacity optical transmission networks: Final report of action cost 239','UZagreb','not-in-selection',1999,'','','journal'),(480,'Unavailability of critical SCADA communication links interconnecting a power grid and a telco network','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2010,'','','journal'),(481,'Understanding the cascading failures in Indian power grids with complex networks theory','ScienceDirect','not-in-selection',2013,'','','journal'),(482,'Universal behavior of load distribution in scale-free networks','APS','not-in-selection',2001,'','','journal'),(483,'Universal robustness characteristic of weighted networks against cascading failure','APS','not-in-selection',2008,'','','journal'),(484,'Usefulness of DC power flow for active power flow analysis with flow controlling devices','IET','not-in-selection',2006,'','','proceedings'),(485,'Vertex overload breakdown in evolving networks','APS','not-in-selection',2002,'','','journal'),(486,'Virtual network embedding through topology-aware node ranking','ACM','not-in-selection',2011,'','','journal'),(487,'Virtual network embedding with coordinated node and link mapping','IEEE','not-in-selection',2009,'','','proceedings'),(488,'Virus spread in networks','IEEE','not-in-selection',2009,'','','journal'),(489,'Vulnerability of state-interdependent networks under malware spreading','ScienceDirect','Vulneravility-of-state',2014,'Computer viruses are evolving by developing spreading mechanisms based on the use of multiple vectors of propagation. The use of the social network as an extra vector of attack to penetrate the security measures in IP networks is improving the effectiveness of malware, and have therefore been used by the most aggressive viruses, like Conficker and Stuxnet. In this work we use interdependent networks to model the propagation of these kind of viruses. In particular, we study the propagation of a SIS model on interdependent networks where the state of each node is layer-independent and the dynamics in each network follows either a contact process or a reactive process, with different propagation rates. We apply this study to the case of existing interdependent networks, namely a Spanish scientific community of Statistical Physics, formed by a social network of scientific collaborations and a physical network of connected computers in each institution. We show that the interplay between layers increases dramatically the infectivity of viruses in the long term and their robustness against immunization.','The paper studies contagion dynamics, they take the particular case of the malware contagion. This paper develops a new formalism that applies to the study of the epidemic spreading in these kind of systems. The idea is to take into account the contagion process. They show the concept of state-interdependent networks (SINs). This is a multi-layered network where on each network there\'s the same amount of nodes and each node has the same id on each network, here there are no links between layers, instead the nodes with the same id share the same \'\'state\'\'. In this paper the states are given by a SIS epidemic model (Infected, susceptible). On this model each layer exhibits a different contagion pattern. The contagion patern is measured over time considering the probability of get infected or the probability of recovery. The robustness of the network is measured through the density of infected nodes. They test their proposal using the Spanish Statistical Physics networks, 2 layers are defined: physical and social. On each layer the authors are nodes. On the physical layer the links represent that they belong to the same university and department or that they belong to the same research center. On the social network the links represent collaboration between authors. The experiments were averaged over 200 realizations and they all start with the network fully infected. The results show that the dynamics of the SIS contagion proces in SINs where the states of the nodes must be layer-independent is equivalent to the spreading in a mono-layer governed by the effective contagion.','journal'),(490,'W32. stuxnet dossier','whitepaper symantec','not-in-selection',2011,'','','whitepaper'),(491,'What energy functions can be minimized via graph cuts?','IEEE','not-in-selection',2004,'','','journal'),(492,'Complex interdependent supply chain networks: Cascading failure and robustness','ScienceDirect','Complex-interdependent',2016,'A supply chain network is a typical interdependent network composed of an undirected cyber-layer network and a directed physical-layer network. To analyze the robustness of this complex interdependent supply chain network when it suffers from disruption events that can cause nodes to fail, we use a cascading failure process that focuses on load propagation. We consider load propagation via connectivity links as node failure spreads through one layer of an interdependent network, and we develop a priority redistribution strategy for failed loads subject to flow constraint. Using a giant component function and a one-to-one directed interdependence relation between nodes in a cyber-layer network and physical-layer network, we construct time-varied functional equations to quantify the dynamic process of failed loads propagation in an interdependent network. Finally, we conduct a numerical simulation for two cases, i.e., single node removal and multiple node removal at the initial disruption. The simulation results show that when we increase the number of removed nodes in an interdependent supply chain network its robustness undergoes a first-order discontinuous phase transition, and that even removing a small number of nodes will cause it to crash.','This paper propos a model for interdependent supply chain network composed by a physical network and a logical network. Each network is slightly different, but both have load capacities on its nodes and edges and the same amount of nodes. The physical network is a directed network representing the physical supply chain (suppliers, manufacterers, etc.) and logical network is a non directed graph. In this framework the model presented follows a one to one relation in the sense that a node in one network is conected to only one node on the other network, these dependencies may be uni or bidirectional. Nodes may fail due to attacks or overloads. A node is considered functional if it belongs to the largest connected component and survives the cascading failures, the rest of the nodes that survive but don\'t belong to the largest connected component are considered partially functional. They tested the robustness of the interdependent supply chain network by removing 1 node on the logical network or a fraction 1-p of it, 1 node on the physical network or a fraction 1-p of it and a fraction 1-p between the 2 networks. The tests performed tunned the parameter of the networks (load capacities) to study the supply chain. On the case of removing a fraction 1-p of nodes these were chosen at random, on descending degree order an on ascending degree order. The comprehensive efficiency index was used to measure robustness as well as transition order studies. On the model the redistribution of loads towards other nodes is given by a probabilty.','journal'),(493,'￼Robustness of interdependent networks with different link patterns against cascading failures','ScienceDirect','Robustness-of-interdependent',2013,'Taking into account the load, the load redistribution, and the node capacity, we study the robustness of two interdependent networks A and B against cascading failures, where each node in network A depends on one node in network B, and vice versa. We adopt three kinds of link patterns between two interdependent networks, i.e., the assortative link (AL), the disassortative link (DL), the random link (RL), where the RA refers to connect randomly two nodes in networks A and B, the AL refers to that high-degree (low-degree) nodes in A network link high-degree (low-degree) nodes in B network, while the DL refers to the fact that high-degree nodes in A network link low-degree nodes in B network. We investigate the robustness of the interdependent networks constructed by two artificial networks and the power grid, taking into account two stages of the cascading propagation. We numerically find that both the different link patterns and the parameters in the cascading model have important effects on dramatically improving the robustness of the interdependent networks against cascading failures. In addition, we obtain the better link pattern and the matching network structure to effectively avoid the cascading propagation.','This paper explores different ways of assigning link patterns for interdependent links. They use assortative, dissasortative and random link patterns. They adopt the normalized avalanche size S to quantify the robustness. They also define capacities and load properties. They say that the cascading failure occur in 2 stages (one for dependence and the other for load failures). When a node fails the load is redistributed between the neighbours of the failed node proportionaly to their capacities. Cai = (1+beta)k^alfa_ai is the capacitie. They also define p(s) to cuantify robustness, p(s) denotes the proportion between the number of the increased failed nodes in the interdependent networks and the number of the failed nodes in the single BA networks (barabasi-albert),  the smaller the value p(s), the stronger the robustness of the interdependent networks against cascading failures.','journal'),(494,'￼Robustness of network of networks with interdependent and interconnected links','ScienceDirect','Robustness-of-network',2014,'Robustness of network of networks (NON) has been studied only for dependency coupling (Gao et al., 2012) and only for connectivity coupling (Leicht and Souza, arxiv:0907.0894). The case of network of networks with both interdependent and interconnected links is more complicated, and also more close to real-life coupled network systems. Understanding the robustness of NON with interdependent and interconnected links is helpful to design resilient infrastructures. Here we develop a framework to study analytically and numerically the robustness of this system with no-feedback and feedback conditions for the case of starlike NON. When assumed that all degree distributions of the connectivity intra and inter-links are Poissonian, we find that the system undergoes from second order through hybrid order to first order phase transition as coupling strength q increases. Additionally, for both conditions, the results suggest that increasing density of connectivity links (intra-connectivity links or inter-connectivity links) can increase the robustness of the system, while the interdependency links decrease its robustness. Furthermore, by comparing critical attacking strength under same parameters for both conditions, we also find that feedback condition of dependency links, in contrast to no-feedback condition, makes the system extremely vulnerable. Although our detailed analysis is for Poisson degree distribution, the theory can be applied to any degree distribution and other basic topological structure of network such like tree-like and loop-like NON.','This network uses a model that can contain more than 2 networks and that posseses 2 kinds of links: connectivity links (that may act as a bridge to unite connected components even on different networks) and dependency links that represent the dependency between nodes (if a node loses its dependency link dies). This model can has different coupling strength, degree distribution, fractions of nodes in one network depending on nodes of other network and it can have or not the feedback condition (no feedback condition = \"one to one\" model). They use percolation threshold to study the robustnes as well as size of the largest connected component. Note here that the largest connected component may include node clusters that within the network appear disconnected but looking at the overall system are connected to the largest connected component through a connectivity link. They define the hybrid percolation transition (there is a discontinuity point but it doesn\'t desintegrate the network to 0). They find that the higher the number of connectivity links the stronger the system (network of networks, NON) but the higher the amount of dependency links the worst the robustners of the NON.','journal'),(495,'Cascading Failures in Interdependent Infrastructures: An Interdependent Markov-Chain Approach','IEEE','7438924',2016,'Many critical infrastructures are interdependent networks in which the behavior of one network impacts those of the others. Despite the fact that interdependencies are essential for the operation of critical infrastructures, such interdependencies can negatively affect the reliability and fuel the cascade of failures within and across the networks. In this paper, a novel interdependent Markov-chain framework is proposed that enables capturing interdependencies between two critical infrastructures with the ultimate goal of predicting their resilience to cascading failures and characterizing the effects of interdependencies on system reliability. The framework is sufficiently general to model cascading failures in any interdependent networks; however, this paper focuses on the electric-cyber infrastructure as an example. Using this framework it is shown that interdependencies among reliable systems, i.e., systems with exponentially distributed failure sizes, can make the individually reliable systems behave unreliably as a whole with power-law failure-size distributions.','Summary: The paper presents a way to model interdependent networks through the use of Makov\'s Chains (Inter-Dependent Markov Chain model). The \'\'robustness\" measurment is given through a reliability measuremente (as specified below). They apply the proposed model to the power system coupled with the communication network and studied various scenarios of reliable and unreliable systems to characterize the distribution of the failure size in coupled systems.\r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nStudies: \r\n- Pstop(Fi) : The probability of transiting from a state with Fi failures and I = 0 to a state with the same number of failures and I = 1, given Fi.\r\n- Rp and Rc: The probabilities of the cascade with x terminal failures in the power grid and y terminal failures in the communication system\r\n- Reliability: effect of the \'\'reliability\'\' on the PMF of the failure size. where reliability is defined as below.\r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"Here, we present an Inter-Dependent Markov Chain (IDMC) model, which provides a probabilistic framework to capture the effects of interdependencies among physical networks on the stochastic dynamics of cascading failures in an abstract setting\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) number of failures in the system, F, and the susceptibility (alternatively, stability) of the system to further failures, I. We term the latter binary state variable the cascade-stability variable, where I = 1 indicates a cascade-stable state and I = 0 indicates otherwise.\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) we define the cascade- stop probability, Pstop, as the probability of transiting from a state with Fi failures and I = 0 to a state with the same number of failures and I = 1. The cascade-stop probability is a function of Fi , i.e., Pstop (Fi ), and it completely characterizes the MC and the cascading-failure behavior of the system\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) the effects of the behavior of one system on another system can be divided into: (1) improve, (2) worsen, and (3) do not change, where the precise meaning of these terms in the MC framework, can be identified with: (1) reducing the probability of an extra failure, (2) increasing the probability of an extra failure, and (3) not changing the probability of an extra failure\" \r\n\r\n\"We define the strength of interdependency between two systems based on two factors: (1) how much the knowledge of the behavior of a system affects the dynamics of the other sys- tem (e.g., the relative change in transition probabilities), and (2) how much memory is required to capture the interdepen- dency effects.\"\r\n\r\n\"We refer to the power system by system A and the communication system by system B. (...) we represent the number of failures in the power grid and in the communication system by the variables x and y, respectively.\" \r\n\r\n\"we define a power-dependency-on-communication function by d.\"\r\n\r\np(x) = Pstop(x) for PG and q(y) for CN (also referred as q and p)\r\n\r\n\"The function d modifies the transition probabilities for the power grid based on the dynamics of the communication MC as shown in (4).\"\r\n\r\n\"In general, the closer the value of d is to zero the more reduction occurs in the reliability of the power grid.\"\r\n\"Rp and Rc are the probabilities of the cascade with x terminal failures in the power grid and y terminal failures in the communication system, respectively.\"\r\n\r\n\"Reliable and Unreliable Systems: We term a system for which the probability distribution of the cascade size follows an exponential distribution a reliable system since the probability of large cascades is small compared to heavy-tail distributions. We term a system with a heavy-tail distribution of the cascade size an unreliable system.\"\r\n\r\n\"Particularly, we consider two types of unreliable systems: (type i) a system for which the probability mass function (PMF) of the cascade size follows power-law distribution, and (type ii) a system for which the PMF of the cascade size has a hump at the tail.\"','journal'),(496,'Supporting differentiated resilience classes in multilayer networks','IEEE','7470832',2016,'The concept of providing differentiated classes of resilient services over communications networks has received a lot of attention in the literature. A number of proposals tried to address the problem by provisioning different classes of services with different protection schemes. However, most of these works are applied to a single layer and lack cross layer coordination in multilayer scenarios. In addition, there is an increasing need for supporting services with very high resilience requirements over future communications networks. This, however, has to be done in a cost efficient manner and without over-engineering the network. In this paper, we introduce a novel approach that simplifies the whole design and achieves both high resilience and differentiation. Our approach, utilizes the spine concept idea of embedding a subnetwork at the physical layer with comparatively high availability link and node values [1]. This lays a foundation for differentiation between multiple classes of flows. Then, cross layer mapping and spine-aware routing are performed in a way that transfers this differentiation capability to the upper layer network and flows. We provide two joint routing-mapping optimization formulations and evaluate their performance in a multilayer scenario.','This paper proposes a way to design robust multilayer networks (physical-logical layers) that require mapping. For this they define the \"spine\" which is a high availability subnetwork embbeded in the phsysical layer. Here the \"dependencies\" between networks are unidirectional since the logic layer is mapped onto the physical layer. There are also two \"flow classes\", one that requires high availability and other that doesn\'t (attempt to simulate diverse requirements on a network).  The robustness is measured by the availability/downtime of the network given the conditions. \r\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nStudies: \r\n- minimization of physical resources used (?)\r\n- resources used (same as above)\r\n- Availability\r\n- comparison with no spine\r\n- effect of classes traffic ratio\r\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"Quality of Resilience (QoR ) describes some parameters such as service availability, recovery time, percentage of recoverable traffic, etc.\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) the Spine concept, a subnetwork structure embedded at the physical layer with higher availability.\"\r\n\r\n\"EDT: Expected downtime in hours per year. Given availability A\"\r\n\r\n\"WP: Working Path, BP: Backup Path\"\r\n\r\n\"We consider a two layer network composed of the physical network on the bottom represented as GP with the set of nodes and links (VP , EP ), and on top the logical network GL represented by the set of logical nodes and links (VL , EL ). We assume that each logical node is connected to its corresponding physical node (i.e., VL = VP ).\"\r\n\r\n\" The spine is defined as a subgraph of the physical network, GP , with a subset of nodes and links (VS,ES) in which VS ⊆ VP and ES ⊂ EP.\"\r\n\r\n\"In this paper, we consider two classes: flows of class-1 (φ = 1) which require high availability levels while class-2 (φ = 2) are of a lesser importance and have no strict availability requirements.\"\r\n\r\n\"The first spine, GS1 , is the spine that maximizes the average WP-BP path-pair availability, with the WP routed on the spine and the BP is routed freely on the network with the condition it be disjoint from the WP. The second spine, GS2 , maximizes the average WP path availability on the spine. The third spine, GS3 , was picked as a compromise solution having availability in between the spines GS1 and GS2 .\"\r\n\r\n\"For the logical layer, we generate a number of k-regular random graphs with the same set of physical nodes, VL = VP  (...)\"\r\n\r\n\"Availability: After solving the optimization problems, we use path and mapping information to calculate the logical links and flows expected downtimes. We only consider links availability (i.e., assuming nodes are perfect). As noted earlier we use ae =0.999 for links on the spine (e ∈ ES ) and ae =0.99 for links off the spine (e ∈ EP but e ̸∈ ES).\" | 497 |\r\n| \"Availability: After solving the optimization problems, we use path and mapping information to calculate the logical links and flows expected downtimes. We only consider links availability (i.e., assuming nodes are perfect). As noted earlier we use ae =0.999 for links on the spine (e ∈ ES ) and ae =0.99 for links off the spine (e ∈ EP but e ̸∈ ES).\"','proceedings'),(501,'Resilience of interdependent communication and power distribution networks against cascading failures','IEEE','7497224',2016,'The operations of many modern cyber-physical systems, such as smart grids, are based on increasingly interdependent networks. The impact of cascading failures on such networks has recently received significant attention due to the corresponding effect of these failures on the society. In this paper, we conduct an empirical study on the robustness of interdependent systems formed by the coupling of power grids and communication networks by putting real distribution power grids to the test. We focus on the assessment of the robustness of a large set of medium-voltage (MV) distribution grids, currently operating live in the Netherlands, against cascading failures initiated by different types of faults / attacks. We consider both unintentional random failures and malicious targeted attacks which gradually degrade the capability of the entire system and we evaluate their respective consequences. Our study shows that current MV grids are highly vulnerable to such cascades of failures. Furthermore, we discover that a small-world communication network structure lends itself to the robustness of the interdependent system. Also interestingly enough, we discover that the formation of hub hierarchies, which is known to enhance independent network robustness, actually has detrimental effects against cascading failures. Based on real MV grid topologies, our study yields realistic insights which can be employed as a set of practical guidelines for distribution system operators (DSOs) to design effective grid protection schemes.','This paper studies the PW-CN system through a one to one model. For this the network is attacked in various different ways (random, targete by some centrality measure). The robustness of the network is measured using the size of the giant component and the communication efficiency. \r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nStudies:\r\n- attacks\r\n- size of giant component\r\n- comunnication efficiency\r\n- number of components \r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"medium-voltage (MV),  high- voltage (HV), distributed (renewable) energy resources (DERs), electric vehicles (EVs), Active Distribution Networks (ADNs), distribution system operators (DSOs), powerline communication (PLC), network of networks (NoN)\"\r\n\r\n\"Our study covers a spectrum of different failure types, ranging from unintentional faults to malicious attacks, each characterized by specific node removal pattern.\"\r\n\r\n\"Additionally, instead of considering one single failure that initiates a cascade of failures, we consider a more general context where multiple cascading failures occur.\"\r\n\r\n\"We consider an interdependent system with two undirected graphs, Gsg = (Vsg,Esg) and Gcom = (Vcom,Ecom), representing the (smart) power grid and communication network respectively.\" \r\n\r\n\"Both networks are equal in size, Nsg = Ncom = N, but they do not necessarily possess the same topologies\"\r\n\r\n\"There is 1-to-1 dependency between nodes in Gsg and Gcom. The dependency is bi-directional (i.e., mutually dependent).\"\r\n\r\n\"Drawing on the observations of real-world interdepen- dent systems reported in [15], we follow the positive degree correlation method and create dependency be- tween nodes with similar level of degrees (...)\"\r\n\r\n\"In this model, a cascading failure begins with the failure of a fraction, 1 − p of nodes from network A. All the links connecting to these failed nodes in network A will thus be down. Further, the nodes in network B depending on these nodes will also fail. Any link connected to these failed nodes in network B will also be removed.\"\r\n\r\n\"The nodes belonging to the largest mutually connected component (i.e., the giant component) retain their functionality while the smaller components fail.\"\r\n\r\n\"To evaluate the impact of cascading failures, we follow the literature to use the size of the giant component which mea- sures the level of connectivity of a network as an evaluation metric.\"\r\n\r\n\"In addition, to understand how the communication functionality degrades, we measure the communication efficiency of the Gcom, η (...) where σi,j is the shortest path length (in hopcount) between node i and j. It measures how fast information spreads in a network. A fully mesh network has η = 1 since all nodes are reachable in one hop (i.e., all node pairs have 1-hop distance).\"\r\n\r\n\"In practice, the functional com-ponent also depends on the actual power source (i.e., P-SS), the re-configurability of the grid (e.g., locations of breakers) as well as the ability to perform islanding operations. (...) , we take a topological approach to draw more general insights that should be applicable to different interdependent systems.\"\r\n\r\n\"Our investigation of the considered NoN’s resilience properties is based on a sequential process where we remove one node after another, with each removal triggering a cascading failure each time. This results in a series of cascading failures. Throughout this process, we track the gradual degradation of the system functionalities in terms of both the above- mentioned metrics.\"','journal'),(502,'Reducing the impact of targeted attacks in interdependent telecommunication networks','IEEE','7500407',2016,'In targeted attacks the network elements are removed with the purpose of maximizing the impact of the attack in the network. When one network interacts with another, the network’s critical parts may change due to failure spreading between them. Thus, it is interesting to identify changes arising in robustness when interdependent networks with similar topological properties interact. We focus on interdependent telecommunication networks modeled as two Erdös-Rényi (ER) random graphs. These graphs are still the most common models for physical or control plane topologies. Previous works have identified that single random networks are highly vulnerable to sequential targeted attacks based on nodal betweenness centrality. In order to interconnect the two ER networks, three link patterns for the interdependency matrix are proposed and the network robustness for each matrix is analyzed in targeted attacks. Results indicate that different interdependency matrices are able to identify new critical parts of the network. Moreover, by selecting a suitable interdependency matrix, the robustness level under targeted attacks can be also improved.','\"In this paper, we focus on interdependent networks created with two telecommunication networks modeled from Erdös-Rényi (ER) random graphs (G1 and G2) and connected by bidirectional inter-links.\"\r\n\r\n\"In targeted attacks the most important nodes, according to one centrality metric, are first removed.\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) the targeted attack over one node in G1 only damages the node that is directly connected in G2, without spreading to others located in G2, and vice versa.\"\r\n\r\n\"To analyze the robustness of G1 when a targeted attack occurs over G2, and vice versa, three link patterns for the interdependency matrix are presented.\"\r\n\r\n\"Suppose one has two undirected networks G1(S,U) and G2(T,V) (...) For simplicity, G1 and G2 have the same number of nodes and each node in G1 depends on the state of only one of the nodes in G2, and vice versa.\"\r\n\r\n\"connectivity matrix A, interdependency matrix B \"\r\n\r\n\"the three link patterns considered for the interdependency matrix are: 1) The High Centrality Dependency Matrix (BHC), (...) the high-central (low-central) nodes in G1 are connected with high-central (low-central) nodes in G2, and vice versa. 2) The Low Centrality Dependency Matrix (BLC) (...) the high-central nodes in G1 are connected to the low-central nodes in G2, and vice versa. 3) The Random Interdependency Matrix (BRA) (...)\"\r\n\r\n\"In order to interconnect the nodes between the two telecommunication networks, for the high (BHC) and low (BLC) centralities matrices, the nodes are ranked by their bc measures. In random interdependency matrix (BRA), the nodes between the networks are interconnected randomly.\"\r\n\r\n\"With the aim of independently analyze the robustness level of each network in a sequential targeted attack by nodal betweenness centrality (bc), the \'average two-terminal reliability\' (ATTR) is selected as metric. (...) ATTR measures the probability of the connectivity between a randomly chosen node pair in a single network, (...) [where c is the number of components, Ki is the number of nodes in component i and N is the number of nodes in the network.] \"','proceedings'),(503,'Shell attack on interdependent networks','IEEE','7553249',2016,'The robustness of networks suffering site or link attacks is a topic of great interest because it is an important issue affecting many real-world networks. The robustness of complex networks under attack is dependent upon the structure of the underlying network and the nature of the attack. However, random attack and hub-targeted attack do not adequately describe many real-world scenarios in which complex networks suffer from localized damage. Nodes within each shell are classified into two categories, protected nodes and unprotected nodes, in this paper. And we propose a kind of attacking mode based on shell structure, which means that when some node (root node) is under attack and malfunction, unprotected nodes of all shells or partial shells within network also fail. And, we numerically and analytically study the system robustness under the attack by taking Erdos-Renyi (ER) network as a example. The results suggest that the robustness of the networks with dependence links relies not only on the number of the dependence links but also on average degree.','This paper uses the same framework used in \'Catastrophic cascade of failures in interdependent networks\' to test \'shell attacks\'\r\n-----------------\r\n\"The shell structure of a network is important for under- standing the transport properties of the network such as the epidemic spread, information diffusion and synchronization processes, where the information or virus spread from a ran- domly chosen root and reach nodes shell after shell.\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) 1 − pl fraction of nodes in network A are removed, be- cause there exists 1-to-1 bidirectional dependency links be- tween all or some of these A-nodes and the nodes in the other network B, so these B-nodes are also removed from the net- work B [4]. We assume that a functional node in network A (B) must belong to the giant component of network A (B). When this cascading process occurs, it will stop if nodes that fail in one step do not cause additional failures.\"','proceedings'),(504,'Reliable communication models in interdependent critical infrastructure networks','IEEE','7573324',2016,'Modern critical infrastructure networks are becoming increasingly interdependent where the failures in one network may cascade to other dependent networks, causing severe widespread national-scale failures. A number of previous efforts have been made to analyze the resiliency and robustness of interdependent networks based on different models. However, communication network, which plays an important role in today’s infrastructures to detect and handle failures, has attracted little attention in the interdependency studies, and no previous models have captured enough practical features in the critical infrastructure networks. In this paper, we study the interdependencies between communication network and other kinds of critical infrastructure networks with an aim to identify vulnerable components and design resilient communication networks. We propose several interdependency models that systematically capture various features and dynamics of failures spreading in critical infrastructure networks. We also discuss several research challenges in building reliable communication solutions to handle failures in these models.','\"For simplicity, we use an example between a communication network and a power grid network, although the models can be extended to other heterogeneous CI (critical infrastructure) networks.\"\r\n\r\n\"We study the interdependency between communication net- work c-network and other heterogeneous critical infrastructure networks. Specifically, we use the interdependency between two networks to represent the models, (...) Without loss of generality, we use power grid network p- network as an example in the rest of the papers to represent the models.\"\r\n\r\n\"The sizes of the two networks may or may not be the same.\"\r\n\r\n\"The interdependency between the networks can be represented in a directed graph G = (V , E ). We use edges\r\nand links interchangeably. V = Vc ∪ Vp is the set of the nodes where Vc is the set of c-nodes and Vp is the set of p-nodes. E = Ec ∪Ep ∪Ecp ∪Epc is the set of edges, where Ec represents the edges between c-nodes, Ep represents the edges between p-nodes, Ecp is the set of edges from c-nodes to p-nodes, and Epc is the set of edges from p-nodes to c-nodes.\"\r\n\r\n\"The Ec and Ep edges are bi-directional.\"\r\n\r\n\"If a c-node ci has an edge to a p-node pi, we call pi a p-neighbor of ci. Similarly, if a p-node pi has an edge to a c node ci, we call the c-node a  c-neighbor of pi . \"\r\n\r\n\"Simple Model: (...) a p-node operates if it receives control signals from at least one c-node and a c-node operates if it receives power from at least one p- node, i.e., each node operates if there is at least one incoming interdependency edge.\"\r\n\r\n\"Weighted Simple Model: We use weighted graph to include the features such as the power supply or demand. In this specific case, it is meaningful to only make the Epc edges weighted and other edges remain the same with the simple model. (...) the number on the links represent the weights as power supply, e.g., in Watts. (...) The weighted simple model can also be useful to also include the backup battery at c-nodes, e.g., uninterrupted power supply (UPS) for the routers.\"\r\n\r\n\"Spread Model: (...) The spread model captures the feature where a faulty node will first spread and cause the failures of the same network. (...) The spread model can be extended in several ways. For instance, a faulty node can spread to all the direct neighbors in the same network, nodes within certain number of hops, etc.\"\r\n\r\n\"Weighted Spread Model: [merge of previous]\"\r\n\r\n\"Cluster Model: The cluster model considers a model based on any of previous models but considers an additional property: only nodes that are mutually dependent are potentially functional.\"\r\n\r\n\"Probabilistic Model: (...) the failures of interdependency edges/nodes are proba-\r\nbilistic in several cases.\"','proceedings'),(505,'Improved percolation theory incorporating power flow analysis to model cascading failures in Cyber-Physical Power System','IEEE','7741419',2016,'The modern power grid is becoming an interdependent Cyber-Physical Power System (CPPS). The worldwide blackouts revealed the mutual interdependences render the CPPS more vulnerable to cascading failures. The percolation theory is a useful tool to analyze and simulate the cascading failure in interdependent networks. However, the current percolation theory is based on purely topological analysis. This paper presents an improved percolation theory which incorporates the AC power flow analysis to model the dynamic developing process of cascading failures in the CPPS. The simulations of cascading failures in the CPPS with various interface and node attack strategies demonstrate that the topological centrality interface strategy shows better robustness, while the topological centrality based node attack could cause heavier damage. In addition, compared with the conventional percolation theory, the improved percolation theory models the cascading failure in the CPPS more exactly and provides more comprehensive indices of the robustness of the CPPS.','Summary: the paper proposes a PW-CN model that considers load failures on the PW due to under or oveload. Different types of coupling are studied and the robustness measure is the relative amount of nodes lost on a cascading failure. The cascading failure starts with the removal of several nodes. \r\n------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nstudies: \r\n- coupling\r\n- avalanche\r\n------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"Cyber-Physical Power System (CPPS)\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) this paper presents an improved percolation theory which incorporates AC power flow analysis to model the dynamic propagation of cascading failures in the CPPS, and studies the robustness of the CPPS to failures and attacks.\"\r\n\r\n\"Cascading failures in the CPPS with various interface and node attack strategies are studied and compared.\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) the purely topological percolation theory without power flow analysis and the improved percolation theory in this paper are also compared.\"\r\n\r\n\" [model] The physical layer is modeled as a weighted graph G =< N,E,W > , where N is the set of nodes (the substations and generation plants), E is the set of edges (the transmission lines), and W is the weighted matrix for the edges. The elements of W are the electrical distances between two ends of the edges and equal to the reciprocal of the reactance of the corresponding edges, w = x−1 , where i and j ij ij are the two ends of the edge [13]. The order of the network is defined as the number of nodes within it.\"\r\n\r\n\"[model] The cyber layer is the Ethernet-based communication network to monitor and control the physical layer, in which the node is the operation center and the edge is the information transmitting media.\"\r\n\r\n\"In this paper, the cyber layer is modeled as a scale-free network using Barabási-Albert model and has the same order as its corresponding physical layer.\"\r\n\r\n\"[model] Two types of unidirectional interdependence connections exist in the CPPS model, which are the power dependency and the control dependency, (...)\"\r\n\r\n\"[model] Power dependency means the power needed by the targeted cyber layer node is provided by the connected physical layer node\"\r\n\r\n\"[model] control dependency means that the targeted physical node is under the monitor and control of the connected cyber layer node.\"\r\n\r\n\"coupling strategies:\r\n- Random interface strategy: The cyber layer node to control each of the physical node is chosen randomly from the cyber layer nodes and vice versa.\r\n- Degree-to-betweenness interface strategy: The nodes in physical and cyber layers are ranked in the betweenness sequence and degree sequence, respectively. The interdependence is modeled through connecting the corresponding nodes in those sequences.\r\n- Topological centrality interface strategy: The topological centrality interface strategy is connecting nodes in the physical layer to corresponding nodes in the cyber layer and these nodes in two layers are ranked in topological centrality sequences. The topological centrality of nodes is the reciprocal\r\nof corresponding diagonal entries of L+ , which is the Moore-Penrose pseudo-inverse matrix of combinatorial Laplacian matrix ( L ) of the graph.\"\r\n\r\n\"[model]  To analyze and model the cascading failure in the CPPS, the nodes in physical and cyber layers operate only if the following two conditions are satisfied:\r\n• The nodes belong to the giant component of its own\r\nlayer.\r\n• For cyber layer nodes, there are at least one power\r\ndependency from functioning physical layer node, and for physical layer nodes, there are at least one control dependency from functioning cyber layer node.\"\r\n\r\n\"[cascading failure process] (...) the AC power flow of the physical layer functioning giant component is to be calculated. If the power flow fails to converge, it means the generators in the giant component can not meet the load demand and then the minimum load shedding is calculated.\"\r\n\r\n\"Then edges capacity check is performed and the over-loaded edges are trigged by their protection system. For the operation security and reliability, the capacity of the edge in the physical layer is set as 80% of its emergency capacity. After cutting the over-loaded edges, the nodes in the giant component need to be calculated again and updated.\"\r\n\r\n\"[robustness metrics] To show the robustness of the interdependent networks in the perspectives of both topology and physical layer functionality, the robustness indices include the ratio of removed nodes in the end of the cascading failure to the total nodes in both the cyber and physical layers (avalanche?) and the\r\nratio of load shedding in the physical layer.\"\r\n\r\n\"[case study] The interdependence between the physical layer and cyber layer is designed as two-to-two unidirectional interdependence, which means that each node in the cyber layer receives power supply from two nodes in the physical layer, one of is the main power supply node and the other one is the back-up, vice versa, each node in the physical layer connects to two cyber layer nodes, one is the main monitor and control node and the other one is the back-up.\"\r\n\r\n\"To decide which interface strategy of the CPPS is more robust, the CPPS is simulated under random cyber layer node attack with three interface strategies\"','proceedings'),(506,'Study of Robustness in Functionally Identical Coupled Networks against Cascading Failures','PLOS ONE','journal.pone.0160545',2016,'\r\nBased on coupled networks, taking node load, capacity and load redistribution between two networks into consideration, we propose functionally identical coupled networks, which consist of two networks connected by interlinks. Functionally identical coupled networks are derived from the power grid of the United States, which consists of many independent grids. Many power transmission lines are planned to interconnect those grids and, therefore, the study of the robustness of functionally identical coupled networks becomes important. In this paper, we find that functionally identical coupled networks are more robust than single networks under random attack. By studying the effect of the broadness and average degree of the degree distribution on the robustness of the network, we find that a broader degree distribution and a higher average degree increase the robustness of functionally identical coupled networks under random failure. And SF-SF (two coupled scale-free networks) is more robust than ER-ER (two coupled random networks) or SF-ER (coupled random network and scale-free network). This research is useful to construct robust functionally identical coupled networks such as two cooperative power grids.','This paper proposes a model to study same-functionality coupled networks. Here, they explore the case of power grids coupled where they transfer load  between them and that causes the cascading failure. The load transfer between network occurs inmediatly. They explore the robustness using the normalized amount of total nodes lost when each node is removed with reposition. They do this for different loads and topologies.\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nstudies:\r\n- load\r\n- topology of nets\r\n\"(...) in this work, two power grids are considered as two independent networks and power transmis- sion lines as the interlinks connecting them. We propose this configuration as functionally identical coupled networks and we aim at studying its robustness.\"\r\n\r\n\"(2) In interdependent networks, a failed node in one of them causes a failure in the corresponding node of the other network. But in functionally identical coupled networks, the only reason a node crashes is that it cannot handle the extra load from nodes directly connected to it.\"\r\n\r\n\"In every network, each node has a load and a finite capacity, in the same way that in a power grid each power station has a load and a finite capacity. The node’s load corresponds to the intensity of electric current flowing in a power station, whereas its capacity corresponds to the biggest load that a power station can handle before breaking down. \"\r\n\r\n\"We assume that the initial load of a node is equal to its degree, and that its capacity is proportional to its initial load.\"\r\n\r\n\"(...)initial load of node Ai in network A is defined as LAi = kAi and initial load of node Bi in network B as LBi = kBi . Similarly, node’s Ai capacity in network A is defined as CAi = (1+β)kAi and node’s Bi capacity in net-work B as CBi  = (1+β)kBi , where β is the tolerance parameter, and β>0\"\r\n\r\n\"The strategy that we propose here consists in randomly removing one node from function- ally identical coupled network.\"\r\n\r\n\"Assuming that the cascading failures are induced by removing node i, and that the size of normal nodes (functional) in functionally identical coupled networks is Si after a cascade failure, we use S = ∑i in AUB(si/(2N)^2) to characterize the robustness of functionally identical coupled networks.\"','journal'),(507,'Redundant Design in Interdependent Networks','PLOS ONE','journal.pone.0164777',2016,'Modern infrastructure networks are often coupled together and thus could be modeled as interdependent networks. Overload and interdependent effect make interdependent networks more fragile when suffering from attacks. Existing research has primarily concentrated on the cascading failure process of interdependent networks without load, or the robustness of isolated network with load. Only limited research has been done on the cascading failure process caused by overload in interdependent networks. Redundant design is a primary approach to enhance the reliability and robustness of the system. In this paper, we propose two redundant methods, node back-up and dependency redundancy, and the experiment results indicate that two measures are effective and costless. Two detailed models about redundant design are introduced based on the non-linear load-capacity model. Based on the attributes and historical failure distribution of nodes, we introduce three static selecting strategies-Random-based, Degree-based, Initial load-based and a dynamic strategy-HFD (historical failure distribution) to identify which nodes could have a back-up with priority. In addition, we consider the cost and efficiency of different redundant proportions to determine the best proportion with maximal enhancement and minimal cost. Experiments on interdependent networks demonstrate that the combination of HFD and dependency redundancy is an effective and preferred measure to implement redundant design on interdependent networks. The results suggest that the redundant design proposed in this paper can permit construction of highly robust interactive networked systems.','This paper uses a simple one to one network with load to test different backup strategies. To appreciate the network robustness G (average size of the largest connected component on each network) is used. The idea is to have low cost options to make the system more robust.\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"in this paper, to suppress over- load failure of nodes, we introduce a novel method-redundant design in construction of interdependent networks and analyze different effects of two kinds of redundant strategies.\"\r\n\r\n\"[model]  Connectivity links (blue or green solid line) in two isolated networks could transfer traffic but dependent links (black dash line) could not. Dependent links between two isolated networks are bidirectional and only provide functional and logical connectivity between two networks. If a node in network NA failed, which would lead to another node in network NB collapsed because of functional dependency, which means interdependent failure.\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) Dou B.[20] pro- posed a non-linear load-capacity model, which seemed more suitable for real system. In this paper, we adopt this model to determine the capacity of nodes (...)\"-> depends on α and β\r\n\r\n\"(...)  the cost of network is depend on nodes capacity, which means that with the increase of α and β, we should allocate more resource on network.\"\r\n\r\n\"Once the load of a node surpass its capacity, it will lead to overload failure, which is another failure mode of node in interdependent network.\"\r\n\r\n\"A small amount of nodes in the network are overload or suffering attack, which may cause cascading failure and lead to further damage.\"\r\n\r\n\"Previous studies proposed that the relative value of average network size after the cascading failure process can be selected to evaluate the robustness of interdependent networks under random/intentional attack[1, 4, 14]. The relative value of average network size after cascading failure (...)\"','journal'),(508,'Operational resilience: concepts, design and analysis','nature','srep19540',2016,'Building resilience into today’s complex infrastructures is critical to the daily functioning of society and its ability to withstand and recover from natural disasters, epidemics, and cyber-threats. This study proposes quantitative measures that capture and implement the definition of engineering resilience advanced by the National Academy of Sciences. The approach is applicable across physical, information, and social domains. It evaluates the critical functionality, defined as a performance function of time set by the stakeholders. Critical functionality is a source of valuable information, such as the integrated system resilience over a time interval, and its robustness. The paper demonstrates the formulation on two classes of models: 1) multi-level directed acyclic graphs, and 2) interdependent coupled networks. For both models synthetic case studies are used to explore trends. For the first class, the approach is also applied to the Linux operating system. Results indicate that desired resilience and robustness levels are achievable by trading off different design parameters, such as redundancy, node recovery time, and backup supply available. The nonlinear relationship between network parameters and resilience levels confirms the utility of the proposed approach, which is of benefit to analysts and designers of complex systems and networks.','This paper presents a way to study resilience as a whole on interdependent and multi-level directed acyclic graphs. The approach takes into account: failure,  cascade, recovery. The robustnness of the system is measured in terms of the \"critical functionality\" which in this case is the amount of nodes on the largest connected component as a function of time and the system  resilience which is evaluated as the integral of the critical functionality’s (K) dependency on time.\r\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nStudies: \r\n- recovery\r\n- critical functionality (in this case size of largest connected component)\r\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"Yet recent publications and guid- ance documents14,15 coalesce around the definition of resilience provided by the National Academy of Sciences (NAS)16: Resilience of a system is its ability “to plan and prepare for, absorb, respond to, and recover from disasters and adapt to new conditions”. (...). The assessment of resilience should therefore identify the critical functionality of a system and evaluate the temporal profile of system recovery in response to adverse events.\"\r\n\r\n\"This paper proposes a methodology for quantifying a system’s resilience that captures the very concept of engi- neering resilience advanced by the NAS27,28 stated above.\"\r\n\r\n\"[RESILIENCE/ROBUSTNESS METRIC]  We make use of the critical functionality (CF) (which has been referred to before as functionality function8, performance29,30, quality18,31,32), defined as a metric of system performance set by the stakeholders, to derive an integrated measure of resilience. One example for CF, among many possible ones, is the percentage of nodes that are functioning. Another is the ratio of a network’s actual flow to its maximum capacity.\"\r\n\r\n\"For application domains, our focus in this paper are the following two classes of models: i) multi-level directed acyclic graphs (DAG)33, and ii) interdependent coupled networks.\"\r\n\r\n\"[DEFINITIONS]: \r\n- A network is modeled as a graph G(N, L) with a set of nodes N connected by links L\r\n- The specification of N and L includes characteristics relevant to resilience, such as capacity, location, and weight of each node and link.\r\n- Let C be the set of temporal decision rules and strategies to be developed in order to improve the resilience of the system during its operation.\r\n- the system must maintain its critical functionality Κ at each time step t, where Κ maps its states or parameters to a real value between 0 and 1.\r\n- class of adverse events (or potential attacks on targeted nodes) E.\r\n- Resilience, denoted by R, is a composite function of the network topological properties and their temporal evolution parameters defined for a certain critical functionality and a class of adverse events E: R=F(N,L,C,E)\r\n- We evaluate R over a certain time interval [0, TC] where TC is the control time41 which can be set a priori, for instance, by stakeholders or estimated as the mean time between adverse events.\r\n- the whole network A is destroyed as a result of the adverse event (pdestr =1)\r\n- number of the backup agents (Nb)\"\r\n\r\n\"[METRIC] Resilience and critical functionality concepts as advanced by the NAS. The system’s resilience is evaluated as the integral of the critical functionality’s (K) dependency on time.\"\r\n\r\n\"we instead simulate the damage to the system from a certain adverse event (regardless of the probability that the event occurs) and define resilience for that particular damage.\"\r\n\r\n\"We assume that homogeneous nodes and links comprising the network have only two possible states: active and inactive, meaning wi (t), πi (t) ∈ {0, 1}\"\r\n\r\n\"[RESILIENCE/ROBUSTNESS METRIC] If we denote the number of active nodes in the system at time t by A(t) and the total number of nodes in the system by N, then the critical functionality simplifies to K (t) = A(t)/N\"\r\n\r\n\"[RESILIENCE/ROBUSTNESS METRIC]  Fig. 8 show the phase diagrams of the dependency of the resilience (calculated as the integral of the CF over the control time) on the model parameters pdestr and Nb. \"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] The second model is derived from the model introduced by Buldyrev et al.34 and developed by Parshani et al.46. They consider a system comprised of two coupled undirected networks (A and B). A certain fraction of nodes in network A depends on nodes in network B (qA) and vice versa (qB). If node n in network A depends on a node m in network B then node m can only depend on node n (or not depend on nodes in network A at all) \"\r\n\r\n\"[recovery] If a node has backup supply and it is connected to its network’s GC it is activated. Once a node is activated it is included in the network’s GC. This causes eventual growth of the giant component of the network A. After that the nodes in the network B that depend on the activated nodes in the network A and are connected to the GC of the network B are also activated and the process propagates in a similar fashion. \"\r\n','journal'),(509,'Recovery of Interdependent Networks','nature','srep22834',2016,'Recent network research has focused on the cascading failures in a system of interdependent networks and the necessary preconditions for system collapse. An important question that has not been addressed is how to repair a failing system before it suffers total breakdown. Here we introduce a recovery strategy for nodes and develop an analytic and numerical framework for studying the concurrent failure and recovery of a system of interdependent networks based on an efficient and practically reasonable strategy. Our strategy consists of repairing a fraction of failed nodes, with probability of recovery γ, that are neighbors of the largest connected component of each constituent network. We find that, for a given initial failure of a fraction 1 − p of nodes, there is a critical probability of recovery above which the cascade is halted and the system fully restores to its initial state and below which the system abruptly collapses. As a consequence we find in the plane γ − p of the phase diagram three distinct phases. A phase in which the system never collapses without being restored, another phase in which the recovery strategy avoids the breakdown, and a phase in which even the repairing process cannot prevent system collapse.','\"Here we introduce a recovery strategy for nodes and develop an analytic and numerical framework for studying the concurrent failure and recovery of a system of interdependent networks based on an efficient and practically reasonable strategy\"\r\n------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nstudies:\r\n------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"[MODEL] Both networks have the same number of nodes N. Within each network the nodes are ran- domly connected through connectivity links with a degree distribution Pi(k), where i = A or B. Pairs of nodes across the two networks are randomly connected one-to-one via bidirectional interdependent links as in Buldyrev et al.20.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] The failure spreads in network A through connectivity links and all the nodes that do not belong to the functional giant component (GC) of network A fail and it is assumed that they become dysfunctional. The failed nodes in network A no longer support their corresponding nodes in network B through their interdependent links, and those nodes in network B that were dependent on the failed nodes in A also fail.\"\r\n\r\n\"We assume that at the initial stage a fraction 1 − p of nodes in network A fail.\"\r\n\r\n\"If the fraction of the initially-failed nodes in A is above 1 − pc, where pc is the critical threshold, and there is no repair strategy, a catastrophic cascade of failures occurs and the system abruptly collapses. Our model assumes a process of recovery that is immediately applied at the first step of the cascade of failures with the objective of avoiding or delaying the collapse of the system.\"\r\n\r\n\" In this process certain failed nodes are recovered according to the following rules: \r\n1. If a failed node in one network is at a distance L = 1 from its GC (we denote the collection of nodes at distance L = 1 from the GC as the boundary of the GC) and has an interdependent link with a failed node in the other network that is also at a distance L = 1 from its corresponding GC, this pair of nodes belongs to the mutual boundary and the two are repaired with a probability γ.\r\n2. If the interdependent node in the other network does not belong to the boundary, none of them is repaired.\"\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','journal'),(512,'The robustness of multiplex networks under layer node-based attack','nature','srep24304',2016,'From transportation networks to complex infrastructures, and to social and economic networks, a large variety of systems can be described in terms of multiplex networks formed by a set of nodes interacting through different network layers. Network robustness, as one of the most successful application areas of complex networks, has attracted great interest in a myriad of research realms. In this regard, how multiplex networks respond to potential attack is still an open issue. Here we study the robustness\r\nof multiplex networks under layer node-based random or targeted attack, which means that nodes just suffer attacks in a given layer yet no additional influence to their connections beyond this layer.\r\nA theoretical analysis framework is proposed to calculate the critical threshold and the size of giant component of multiplex networks when nodes are removed randomly or intentionally. Via numerous simulations, it is unveiled that the theoretical method can accurately predict the threshold and the size of giant component, irrespective of attack strategies. Moreover, we also compare the robustness of multiplex networks under multiplex node-based attack and layer node-based attack, and find that layer node-based attack makes multiplex networks more vulnerable, regardless of average degree and underlying topology.','Summary: This paper takes the approach of \'multiplex networks\' where the nodes are the same but they belong to 2 or more different networks or layers. Here the nodes splitted into layers. The multiplex node contains all the \'instances\' of a node, while a layer node just considers the conections on the layer it belongs to. If a layer node is removed, the conections with its neighbours is lost, but the other layers of the same node are not affected as long as they\'re part of the GCC.\r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nStudies: \r\n- Size of giant component\r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"The giant component naturally consists of a set of connected multiplex nodes. A pair of multiplex nodes are regarded to have connection if there exists at least one type of link between them. Therefore, attacking some layer nodes may not destroy their connection with other nodes, and the set of nodes that remains at the end of damage is the mutually connected giant component (see Fig. 2 for schematic illustration).\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] we term them as multiplex node and layer node, respectively. The former points to the node which connects its neighbors via all the types of links, like node 3 of Fig. 1(a), whose neighbors are 1, 5 and 4 via blue and black links. While the latter is the partial case of multiplex node and just considers the local connection topology of a given node on one layer.\"\r\n\r\n\"(here the removal of a multiplex node means all its replicas in network layers are pruned)\"\r\n\r\n\"[METRIC] The size RLR of giant component in dependence on removal probability φ1 LR and φ2 LR for layer 12\r\nnode-based random attack.\"\r\n','journal'),(513,'Cascading failures in coupled networks with both inner-dependency and inter-dependency links','nature','srep25294',2016,'We study the percolation in coupled networks with both inner-dependency and inter-dependency links, where the inner- and inter-dependency links represent the dependencies between nodes in the same or different networks, respectively. We find that when most of dependency links are inner- or inter-ones, the coupled networks system is fragile and makes a discontinuous percolation transition. However, when the numbers of two types of dependency links are close to each other, the system is robust\r\nand makes a continuous percolation transition. This indicates that the high density of dependency\r\nlinks could not always lead to a discontinuous percolation transition as the previous studies. More interestingly, although the robustness of the system can be optimized by adjusting the ratio of the two types of dependency links, there exists a critical average degree of the networks for coupled random networks, below which the crossover of the two types of percolation transitions disappears, and the system will always demonstrate a discontinuous percolation transition. We also develop an approach to analyze this model, which is agreement with the simulation results well.','This paper studies the case of a network that can have inner and inter dependency links. If there are only inter-dependency links it becomes a one to one model. The nodes remain functional if they belong to the largest connected component and the dependency link stablishes reciprocal dependence. In this case to study the coupling the amount of inter-dependency links must be studied. Each node has a dependency link that can be use inner or inter network.\r\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nStudies: \r\n- percolation\r\n- size of giant component\r\n- coupling (β)\r\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"[MODEL] We consider two coupled networks A and B with degree distributions pkA and pkB, respectively, and each node has exactly one dependency link (inner- or inter- dependency link), where the dependency link means that the two nodes connected by it depend on each other, one of which fails, the other will fail too.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] Assuming that the two networks have the same size N, there are N dependency links in the network system.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] Specifically, a fraction β of the dependency links are set as the inter-dependency links, others are the inner-dependency links. For inter-dependency links, the two stubs (nodes) are chosen randomly in the two net- works, respectively, and in the same networks for inner-dependency links. When β → 0, there is no dependency between the two networks and the model will reduce to the model of the single network with dependency link density q = 1 in ref. 28. When β → 1, our model will reduce to the original model of interdependent network proposed in ref4 (Buldyrev one to one)\"\r\n\r\n\"We want to study the robustness of such coupled system after an initial attack of a fraction, 1 − p, of nodes in network A.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] The failure of a node in network A will lead to the failure of its dependency partner no matter it is in network A or network B, even though it still connects to the network by connectivity links.\"\r\n\r\n\"[METRIC] Here, we focus on the size of the giant component of the two networks, SA and SB, which are the probability that a randomly chosen node belongs to the giant component of the final network A or B, respectively. Note that SA is generally different from SB due to the initial node removal.\"','journal'),(514,'Impact of Degree Heterogeneity on Attack Vulnerability of Interdependent Networks','nature','srep32983',2016,'The study of interdependent networks has become a new research focus in recent years. We focus on one fundamental property of interdependent networks: vulnerability. Previous studies mainly focused on the impact of topological properties upon interdependent networks under random attacks, the effect of degree heterogeneity on structural vulnerability of interdependent networks under intentional attacks, however, is still unexplored. In order to deeply understand the role of degree distribution and in particular degree heterogeneity, we construct an interdependent system model which consists of two networks whose extent of degree heterogeneity can be controlled simultaneously by a tuning parameter. Meanwhile, a new quantity, which can better measure the performance of interdependent networks after attack, is proposed. Numerical simulation results demonstrate that degree heterogeneity can significantly increase the vulnerability of both single and interdependent networks. Moreover, it is found that interdependent links between two networks make the entire system much more fragile to attacks. Enhancing coupling strength between networks can greatly increase the fragility of both networks against targeted attacks, which is most evident under the case of max-max assortative coupling. Current results can help to deepen the understanding of structural complexity of complex real-world systems.','Summary: this paper studies different parameters on single networks, partially coupled network and fully dependent networks. It plays with the coupling (determined as assortative or disassortative) and the heterogeneity degree of the nodes.\r\nstudies:\r\n- coupling (from single net to fully dependent + assortative/dissasortative)\r\n- length (path length)\r\n\r\n\"In this study, we continually focus on the effect of degree distribution on attack vulnerability of single and interdependent networks.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] Following the framework established by Buldyrev et al.26, A partially interdependent system composed of two networks is proposed. (...) Apparently, as p is changed from 0 to 1, the extent of heterogeneity of degree distributions of each network is changed greatly, i.e. a higher p makes corresponding network become more heterogeneous concerning degree distribution.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] Note that only one-to-one and symmetric interdependency is considered, which means that node ai in network A only depends on one node bj in B and vice visa. For partially coupling, only a fraction q of nodes in network A and B depends on each other. 0 ≤ q ≤ 1 and q = 1 corresponds to the case of fully coupling.\"\r\n\r\n\"[METRIC] A New Vulnerability Measure - efficiency loss(el). Communication efficiency is one of the important quantities to measure how efficiently the information is exchanged over the whole network21,40. Suppose that information is exchanged between every pair of nodes and transmitted along the shortest path connecting them, communication efficiency εij is assumed to be inversely proportional to the shortest distance: εij = 1/lij, here, lij denotes the length of shortest path between nodes i and j. Thus, global communication efficiency ε of network G is defined as the average of εij over all pair of nodes, (...)  Once ε(G) is defined as a measure of performance of network G, the damage caused by the removal of some components(node and/or edges) can be naturally evaluated by the a new measure, efficiency loss(el), (...). where ε(G0) is the efficiency of the initial network before any attack and ε(Gf) is the final efficiency that is reached by the network due to the breakdown.\"\r\n\r\n\"after a fraction f of nodes removed from the networks.\"','journal'),(515,'Cascading failures in coupled networks: The critical role of node-coupling strength across networks','nature','srep35352',2016,'The robustness of coupled networks against node failure has been of interest in the past several years, while most of the researches have considered a very strong node-coupling method, i.e., once a node fails, its dependency partner in the other network will fail immediately. However, this scenario cannot cover all the dependency situations in real world, and in most cases, some nodes cannot go so far as to fail due to theirs self-sustaining ability in case of the failures of their dependency partners. In this paper, we use the percolation framework to study the robustness of interdependent networks with weak node- coupling strength across networks analytically and numerically, where the node-coupling strength\r\nis controlled by an introduced parameter α. If a node fails, each link of its dependency partner will be removed with a probability 1−α. By tuning the fraction of initial preserved nodes p, we find a rich phase diagram in the plane p−α, with a crossover point at which a first-order percolation transition changes to a second-order percolation transition.','\r\n------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nStudies:\r\n- size of giant component\r\n- percolation\r\n-coupling\r\n------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\n\"In this paper, we will propose a model to study the robustness of interdependent networks with weak node-coupling strength between networks. By using the percolation theory31–34, we analytically calculate the discontinuous and continuous percolation transition points of our proposed model to validate the simulation results.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] Assuming that ai from network A fails, each connectivity link of its dependency partner bi in network B will be broken with a probability 1−α, where the introduced parameter α controls the impacts of the failure of its dependency partner. Similarly, if a node in network B fails, the connections of its dependency partner in network A will be also cut off as the same way. When α → 1, the failures cannot spread across the net- works. When α → 0, our model will reduce to the original model of interdependent networks proposed in ref. 9. (Buldyrev, Catastrophic)\"\r\n\r\n\"Therefore, we can also define the link-removal probability 1−α as the node-coupling strength of two interde- pendent nodes.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] (...) we destroy a fraction 1−p of randomly selected nodes in network A. As a result, the failures of nodes or their connectivity links may cause the other nodes to disconnect from the largest cluster of network A. In the next stage, each connection of a node with a failed dependency partner will fail with a probability 1−α.\"\r\n\r\n\"[METRIC]  The cascade ends until no further splitting and node removal can occur. In our study, the sizes of giant components SA and SB for the final networks A and B are considered as the key quantities as the previous works.\"\r\n\r\n\"[DEFINITION] Let RA be the probability that a randomly chosen link in network A leads to the giant\r\ncomponent. Similarly, RB is the probability that a randomly chosen link in network B leads to the giant compo-\r\nnent.\"\r\n\r\n\"Since the sizes of giant components SA and SB depend on the auxiliary parameters RA and RB directly, we discuss the phase transition of the system by using the parameters RA and RB.\"','journal'),(516,'Cascade-robustness optimization of coupling preference in interconnected networks','ScienceDirect','cascade-robustness',2016,'Recently, the robustness of interconnected networks has attracted extensive attentions, one of which is to investigate the influence of coupling preference. In this paper, the memetic algorithm (MA) is employed to optimize the coupling links of interconnected networks. Afterwards, a comparison is made between MA optimized coupling strategy and traditional assortative, disassortative and random coupling preferences. It is found that the MA optimized coupling strategy with a moderate assortative value shows an outstanding performance against cascading failures on both synthetic scale-free interconnected networks and real-world networks. We then provide an explanation for this phenomenon from a micro-scope point of view and propose a coupling coefficient index to quantify the coupling preference. Our work is helpful for the design of robust interconnected networks.','Summary: \"In this paper, we design a specific MA to optimize the coupling links of interconnected networks and com- pare the MA optimized coupling strategy with traditional assortative, disassortative and random coupling preferences. It is found that the MA optimized coupling strategy with moderate assortative value can better enforce the network robustness against cascading failures. Afterwards, an explanation from a micro-point of view is provided and an experiment on real-world is investigated.\"\r\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nStudies:\r\n- size of giant component\r\n- coupling\r\n- load (tolerance parameter α)\r\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"[MODEL] Networks A and B are coupled by interconnected links. Coupling probability p = 2nc/N is defined as the ratio of the number of in- terconnected links nc to the network size N/2. Each node has at most one interconnected link.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] In the cascading model, the node load can be calculated by be- tweenness centrality if the traffic flow transmits along the shortest path. (...) The node capacity Ci is the maximum load that the node i can deal with. (...) where α is the tolerance parameter and Li is the initial load of node i.\"\r\n\r\n[MODEL] links are one to one\r\n\r\n\"[NODE REMOVAL] Initially, the highest-load node in the interconnected network is removed. The node load is then recalculated. If one node’s load is beyond its capacity, it will be removed from the system and the load will be updated. Repeat this step until there is no more overloaded nodes.\"\r\n\r\n\"[DEFINITION] \r\nThere are three common coupling preferences, namely assorta- tive, disassortative and random coupling:\r\n\r\n- Assortative coupling.:Couple the heaviest load node in network A with the heaviest load node in network B. Then couple the sec- ond heaviest load node in network A with the second heaviest load node in network B, and so on. Repeat this process until pN/2 cou- pling links are added.\r\n\r\n- Disassortative coupling: Couple the heaviest load node in net- work A with the lightest load node in network B. Then couple the second heaviest load node in network A with the second lightest load node in network B, and so on. Repeat this process until pN/2 coupling links are added.\r\n\r\n- Random coupling: Randomly choose a node in network A and a node in network B. If neither of them has a coupling link, then couple them. Repeat this process until pN/2 coupling links are added.\"\r\n\r\n\"[METRIC] Following common practices, only nodes in giant component remain functional after cascading process. Therefore, the proportion of the giant component to the initial network size is a natural measure of network robustness,\"\r\n','journal'),(517,'Fuzzy-information-based robustness of interconnected networks against attacks and failures','ScienceDirect','Fuzzy-information',2016,'Cascading failure is fatal in applications and its investigation is essential and therefore became a focal topic in the field of complex networks in the last decade. In this paper, a cascading failure model is established for interconnected networks and the associated data-packet transport problem is discussed. A distinguished feature of the new model is its utilization of fuzzy information in resisting uncertain failures and malicious attacks. We numerically find that the giant component of the network after failures increases with tolerance parameter for any coupling preference and attacking ambiguity. Moreover, considering the effect of the coupling probability on the robustness of the networks, we find that the robustness of the assortative coupling and random coupling of the network model increases with the coupling probability. However, for disassortative coupling, there exists a critical phenomenon for coupling probability. In addition, a critical value that attacking information accuracy affects the network robustness is observed. Finally, as a practical example, the interconnected AS-level Internet in South Korea and Japan is analyzed. The actual data validates the theoretical model and analytic results. This paper thus provides some guidelines for preventing cascading failures in the design of architecture and optimization of real-world interconnected networks.','Summary: \"(...)this paper considers cascading failures in a double-layer network due to traffic overloading, taking into account the global dynamic characteristics of the interconnected network.\" \"Inspired by the investigations of fuzzy-information-based attacks considered in single networks [19,20], and by the newly-proposed concept of interconnected networks [30–36] in the field of complex networks, this paper studies the robustness of interconnected networks, using the familiar Barabasi–Albert (BA) network [37] as a platform, for fuzzy- information-based attacks in terms of cascading failures due to traffic overloading. For this purpose, the traffic flow transport model [1] will be adopted. If one node fails, it may likely change the traffic flow paths between itself and other remote nodes thereby causing global failures. In this paper, the critical threshold of removing nodes is found, over which the networks will breakdown. Moreover, the robustness of a network with different coupled preferences and different coupling probabilities is examined in detail. Finally, an application to the interconnected AS-level Internet of South Korea and Japan is demonstrated.\"\r\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nstudies:\r\n- size of giant component\r\n- coupling\r\n- information\r\n- percolation (they study percolation threshold even though they don\'t refer to it in those terms)\r\n- real world tests(?)\r\n- node removal (everyone does this tho)\r\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"[MODEL] In this model, as mentioned above, only the case of two BA networks is considered here because it can represent the heterogeneity of many real-world networks [37]. Label the two networks as A and B. Without loss of generality, the number of nodes in the coupled networks A and B is assumed to be the same, NA = NB = N, with the same degree distribution.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] The two BA networks are interconnected by some links. These links provide paths for the traffic flow between the two coupled networks. Data packets can be delivered along the links between the two networks. A coupling probability p (0 ≤ p ≤ 1) is used. It can be described as ‘the number of interconnected links divided by the network size N’. Assume that each node has at most one interconnected link to the other network.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] In the interconnected network, if some nodes of one network fail, then the nodes of the other network may also fail, due to cascading reactions and failure propagation from one network to another, thus leading to catastrophic failures eventually. To study these cascading failures caused by traffic overload dynamics, we assume that the load on one node can be redistributed to anywhere in the whole interconnected network through connecting links.\"\r\n\r\n\"[DEFINITION] To describe the new model, we introduce three coupling preferences based on load distribution in a BA scale-free network [23].\r\n• Assortative coupling pattern: The nodes of network A are sorted in the descending order according to their loads, labeled as x1 , x2 , . . . , xn , where if some nodes have the same load, then randomly arrange them; nodes in network B are sorted in the same way, labeled as y1 , y2 , . . . , yn . Connect x1 with y1 , connect x2 with y2 , and so on. Finally, randomly connect N × p links between networks A and B.\r\n• Disassortative coupling pattern. The nodes of network A are sorted in the descending order according to their loads, labeled as x1, x2, . . . , xn. On the contrary, nodes in network B are sorted in the ascending order, labeled as y1, y2, . . . , yn. Connect x1 with y1, connect x2 with y2, and so on. Finally, randomly connect N × p links between the networks A and B.\r\n• Random coupling pattern. In each of the two networks, randomly select one node respectively. If neither of them has an interconnected link, then connect them. Thus, a total of N × p links will be connected randomly between the networks A and B.\"\r\n\r\n\"betweenness of node i is used to evaluate its load in the whole networks, (...)\"\r\n\r\n\"The capacity of node i is denoted by Ci. When the load of a node exceeds its capacity, it will fail. Ci = (1 + β)Li. Here, constant β ≥ 0 is the tolerance (or redundancy) parameter and Li is the initial load of node i.\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) here the traffic load is distributed based on the shortest-path routing rule, i.e. the betweenness of the nodes. Therefore, the removal of any one node may affect all nodes in the network.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] The dynamical process of the cascading failure can be described as follows: when one node is removed, this can change the shortest paths between other nodes. The data-packets through these nodes have to change their paths to arrive to the destination nodes, consequently the loads of other nodes will be changed (increased). Those nodes that loads exceed these capacities will fail, it can trigger load redistribution over and over again through the whole network, until the network reaches a final stable state.\"\r\n\r\n\"The relative size of the remaining giant component G in network is usually used to measure the functional integrity and robustness of a network. G =N\'/N where N and N ′ respectively represent the size (number of nodes) of the original network and the size of the giant component of the network after failures.\"\r\n\r\n\"[DEFINITION] Let α be the ambiguity of the information.\"\r\n\r\n\"Then, the interest is on the relationship between the giant component G and the ambiguity α based on the three coupling preferences.\"\r\n\r\n\"[DEFINITION] The name of ‘‘fuzzy-information-based attack’’ refers to the situations between these two extreme cases. (targeted with full info, random)\"\r\n\r\n\"[DEFINITION] the removal fraction f \"\r\n\r\n','journal'),(518,'Percolation-cascading in multilayer heterogeneous network with different coupling preference','ScienceDirect','percolation-cascad',2016,'[ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT]\r\n\r\nMultilayer network with different coupling preference is often used to study complex systems. In this paper we mainly focus on percolation-cascading process in multilayer heterogeneous networks including BA-BA, ER-ER, BA-ER. We put forward our percolation-cascading model and from calculation of Xn and Zn we can get resulting size of mutual largest component in different layers. Refer to Newman’s definition of assortativity we design a stochastic structural algorithm to generate dependency edges between layers from which we get networks with different coupling coefficient. Simulation shows that assortative network in percolation-cascading process performs better and when the layers of multilayer network meet with BA network the robustness of the network increases.','[ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT]\r\n\r\nSummary: \"In this paper we study percolation process in multilayer network under different coupling preferences. Besides the connection between layers are considered as a cascading process. We put forward three types of coupling preferences includes Random Coupling Preference (RCP), Assortative Coupling Preference (ACP) and Disassortative Coupling Preference (DCP). In this paper we mainly focus on BA network and ER network. We deduce the size of mutual largest component of multilayer and give the accurate theoretical solution of three types of heterogeneous multilayer network. From simulation we verify our correctness of derivation. We can also find that assortative multilayer network is more robust and when layers of multilayer network meet with BA network the performance of the network to percolation is better compared with ER network which can give guidance to network construction.\"\r\n\r\n\"percolation is mainly in the same layer and cascading happens between different layers. To study dynamic process of multilayer network percolation-cascading process must be considered.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] We set the connects between layers is one-to-one\"\r\n\r\nHere assortativity is studied. Assortativity/dissasortativity is stablished by degree.\r\n\r\n\"In the model each node has a link with just one node in each of the other layer. We use 1-p is the proportion of deleted nodes, so p is the proportion of remaining nodes.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] Also have f is the proportion of protected nodes. Protected nodes’ edges will not be deleted during cascading process. At the beginning of the percolation process we randomly delete 1-p fraction of nodes in one layer and dependent nodes in other layers. Here the deleted nodes are irrespective of f invulnerable nodes.\"\r\n\r\n\"[CASCADING]\r\nStep 1: Randomly damage 1-p fraction nodes in multilayer network.\r\nStep 2: Find all the nodes in multilayer which have no adjacent node, delete these nodes and its dependent nodes.\r\nStep 3: Repeat step 2 until the nodes in multilayer network cannot be deleted any more.\r\nStep 4: Calculate the remaining nodes in mutual largest component.\" \r\n\r\n\"[DEFINITION] Here we define the probability S that a randomly chosen node belongs to the resulting mutual largest component at the end of percolation-cascading process.\"','journal'),(519,'Reliability analysis of interdependent lattices','ScienceDirect','reliability-analys',2016,'Network reliability analysis has drawn much attention recently due to the risks of catastrophic damage in networked infrastructures. These infrastructures are dependent on each other as a result of various interactions. However, most of the reliability analyses of these interdependent networks do not consider spatial constraints, which are found important for robustness of infrastructures including power grid and transport systems. Here we study the reliability properties of interdependent lattices with different ranges of spatial constraints. Our study shows that interdependent lattices with strong spatial constraints are more resilient than interdependent Erdös–Rényi networks. There exists an intermediate range of spatial constraints, at which the interdependent lattices have minimal resilience.','Summary: \"In this paper, we study the influence of the spatial constraints on the reliability of interdependent spatial networks, in which each component has a lifetime. Comparing interdependent lattices with interdependent ER networks, we find that interdependent lattices with strong spatial constraints are more resilient than interdependent ER networks. When the interdependent length is around an intermediate level, the interdependent lattices are the most vulnerable.\"\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nStudies:\r\n- lifetime\r\n- size of giant component\r\n- length\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"[MODEL] (...) we consider two lattices coupled by interdependent links within a spatial length r to study the reliability properties of the system, comparing with that of interdependent ER networks.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] each node is connected with its four neighbors in the same lattice by connectivity links and coupled with a node in the other lattice by an interdependent link. A node i located at (xi,yi) in network A is coupled with one and only one node j located at (xj , yj ) in network B with the condition:\r\n|xi −xj|≤r and |yi −yj|≤r.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] We assign a lifetime to each node according to a given distribution. As time evolves, nodes in the networks fail due to their lifetimes. \"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] If a node does not belong to the giant component of the network, it also fails.\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) we assume that the time scale of cascading process is negligible comparing to node lifetime.\"\r\n\r\n\"When the size of the giant component falls below a given small value GT , we consider that the network cannot operate normally and collapses. Here GT represents an arbitrary threshold for the network’s giant component, which is to be set according to the network operator’s requirements for business/service continuity in practice.\"\r\n\r\n\"we define the reliability of interdependent network system as:\r\nR(t) = 1 − lim (n(t)/S) (2) s→∞\r\nwhere n(t ) is the number of realizations of which the system collapses before time t and S is the total number of realizations.\"','journal'),(520,'Robustness of single and interdependent scale-free interaction networks with various parameters','ScienceDirect','robustness-of-singl',2016,'The robustness of scale-free networks has attracted increasing attentions recently. It has been shown that scale-free networks are tolerant to random failures but fragile under malicious attacks. However, most existing studies focus on scale-free networks with fixed exponent (around 3) and assortativity (around 0), and the relationship between robustness and these parameters has not been studied systematically. Therefore, in this paper, we study the change of robustness along with different parameters, including scaling exponent and assortativity, of scale-free networks; moreover, the robustness of interdependent networks is also studied. In the experiments, synthetic single scale-free networks with varying scaling exponents are constructed and adjusted to fix assortativity. Several measures are adopted to estimate the robustness of networks under malicious and random attacks. Then, interdependent networks with varying parameters are constructed and their robustness against malicious attacks is studied. The results show that there is a positive correlation between robustness against node attacks and the scaling exponent as well as assortativity, and the positive correlation also exists in interdependent networks.','Summary:  \"(...) in this paper, we focus on the robustness of scale-free networks with different α and r, and both malicious and random attacks are studied. Besides the robustness on single networks, in this paper, we also study the effect of network parameters on the robustness of independent networks. Different scale-free networks with various parameters are constructed as interdependent pairs, and the malicious nodal attacks are studied.\"\r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nStudies:\r\n- size of giant component\r\n- parameters of single net (layer)\r\n- coupling\r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"[METRIC] The size of the largest component after destruction is the measurement of robustness of interdependent networks.\"\r\n\r\n\"[METRIC]  In this paper, we focus on malicious attack on interdependent networks, and the fraction of giant mutually connected component pθ is taken as the measurement of robustness.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] The model of interdependent networks, proposed by Buldyrev et al. in Ref. [7], consists of two networks, A and B, with the same number of nodes N . (...)\"\r\n\r\n\" For every parameter combination, two networks (A and B) with the same parameter (N, α and r) are associated with each other; that is, each node in network A chooses one node in network B to make bidirectional links as described in Section 2.2.\"\r\n\r\n\"In the experiments, we record the fraction of giant mutually connected component (pθ ) under removing fraction of 1-p nodes in the network, and the robustness of different network can be measured by the tendency of corresponding curve.\"\r\n\r\n\"Here, we mainly focus on malicious attacks on nodes.\"\r\n\r\n\"Because of the randomness of dependency between nodes in interdependent networks, the functionality of a high-degree node in network A may rely on a high-degree in network B, resulting in quick decomposition both in networks A and B under malicious attacks. According to this, we sort the degree index in each network, and make bidirectional links under the restriction of degree index. Here, we employ three methods of link-construction strategies, (1) keeping nodes with the same degree index connected, (2) keeping randomly as above, and (3) keeping nodes with inverse index connected. The numerical results of different link-constructions are shown in Fig. 14 (N = 1500, α = 3, and r = 0).\"\r\n','journal'),(521,'Targeted attack on networks coupled by connectivity and dependency links','ScienceDirect','targeted-attack-on',2016,'Coupled systems used to increase capacity were shown beneficial as long as it does not open pathways to cascades. Previous studies on the robustness of coupled networks except for interdependent networks are almost the cases of random attack. Many challenges remain exist in targeted-attack problem of coupled networks. Since nodes within coupled networks show different functions for each network, this paper both analytically and numerically analyzed the robustness of coupled networks under three types of targeted attacking strategies, including attacking on nodes by considering internal and external degree, internal degree only, and external degree only. For coupled network with both interdependent and interconnected links, all degree distributions of intra- and interconnectivity links are Poissonian, we find the system undergoes from second to first order phase transition as coupling strength q increases. The fraction of nodes in the giant component P∞ at stable state, the critical phase transition threshold pc (first order threshold pIc and second order threshold pIIc ), and the critical point (pc , qc ) separating the first and second order phase transitions are analytically obtained for three types of attacking strategies with attacking probability parameter α = 0,1. We also find the system becomes more vulnerable as the average degree of intra-links k ̄ or inter-links K ̄ decreases. Therefore, the minimum average degrees k ̄min and K ̄min to maintain the system stable are obtained for the case of α = 0, 1. Moreover, we discussed three typical cases of coupled networks, interdependent networks (K ̄ = 0), interacting networks (q = 0) and bipartite network (k = 0, q = 0), the analytical expressions of P∞, pc and (pc , qc ) (only for interdependent) are given respectively. Besides, we study the equivalence relations between interdependent networks and coupled networks with connectivity and dependency links for the same pc . The results imply that we can adjust the parameters q, k ̄ and K ̄ to make the two systems have the same robustness. Moreover, the results imply that one should not only protect nodes with high degree of intra-links or inter-links, but also defend nodes, the sum of whose degree of intra-links and inter-links is big, can avoid the system becoming vulnerable.','Summary: In this paper, we study the robustness of networks coupled by connectivity and dependency links under three types of targeted-attacking strategies, including attacking on nodes by considering internal and external degree, internal degree only, and external degree only.\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nstudies:\r\n- percolation\r\n- coupling\r\n- size of giant component\r\n-tergeted attacks\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"Isolated nodes play an important role in coupled networks robustness, especially in interdependent networks. For instance, one isolated node, which is not connected to any other nodes within network, but depends upon one functional hub node of the other network. If this isolated node is initially removed, the hub node of the other network is also removed, as an outcome, cascading failures occur.\"\r\n\r\n\"[DEFINITION] (...)  Wα (kin , kout ), which represents the probability that a node with inter-degree kin and intra-degree kout has been removed, is proposed, (...)\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] Here we consider a system of two networks, A and B, coupled by both dependency and connectivity links. The dependency strengths of A and B are qA and qB separately.\"\r\n\r\n\"Fig. 1(b) (Fig. 2(b)) shows that for fixed K ̄ (k ̄), there exists a critical threshold of qc of coupling strength that changes for different k ̄ (K ̄ ). When q > qc , the system exhibits a first order phase transition at pIc . When q < qc , the system shows a second order phase transition at pII c.\"','journal'),(522,'The effect of capacity redundancy disparity on the robustness of interconnected networks','ScienceDirect','the-effect-of-capac',2016,'Cascading failures in interconnected networks have received more and more attention. In previous works, the basic assumption is that networks share the same capacity redundancy. However, this setting cannot capture the real case very well. Hence, in this paper, we analyze the effect of capacity redundancy disparity on the robustness of interconnected networks. In isolated networks, it is well known that the complex network’s robustness can be improved by increasing its capacity redundancy. In interconnected networks where two networks share the same capacity redundancy, the similar result holds. Yet this result is not necessarily true in interconnected networks where two networks are different in capacity redundancy. We find that when the capacity redundancy of one network is fixed, the robustness of the whole system may not follow another network’s capacity redundancy. More specifically, when the fixed network’s capacity redundancy is very small or very large, the robustness of the whole system increases as another network’s capacity redundancy increases. But there exists a certain range within which the increase of one network’s capacity redundancy results in the robustness decline of the whole system. This counterintuitive feature appears under different coupling patterns such as assortative, disassortative, or random coupling. This result advances our understanding of the robustness of interconnected networks.','Summary: \"In this paper, we try to explore the effect of network capacity redundancy disparity on cascading failures, and display the robustness of interconnected networks under such a more realistic condition. We will show that our common sense from isolated complex networks may become invalid in this interconnected networks case.\"\r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nstudies:\r\n- coupling \r\n- capacity/load\r\n- size of giant component\r\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] Herethesetwonetworks are fully coupled by interconnected links, and each node has one and only one interconnected link.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] In interconnected networks, interconnected links work exactly as same as the links within each complex network. That is to say, traffic (such as data packets in communication networks) can be transmitted from one network to another through interconnected links. In this way, once the interconnected links are added, the whole system works as a big network.\"\r\n\r\n\"[COUPLING] As mentioned in previous studies, coupling patterns, i.e., the ways to add interconnected links have great impact on the interconnected networks’ robustness. Here we consider three kinds of coupling patterns which are described as follows [47]:\r\n• Random coupling. We randomly choose a node in each network. If neither of these two nodes has the interconnected link, then connect them. Otherwise, do not connect them. Repeat this process until all interconnected links are added.\r\n• Assortative coupling. We sort nodes in networks A and B respectively, both in the descending order of loads, labeled as\r\na1 (b1 ), a2 (b2 ), . . . , aNA (bNB ). If two or more nodes share the same load, they are sorted at random. Then connect a1 with\r\nb1, a2 with b2, and so on. Repeat this process until all interconnected links are added.\r\n• Disassortative coupling. We sort nodes in both networks as mentioned above, and connect a1 with bNB , a2 with bNB −1 ,\r\nand so on. Repeat this process until all interconnected links are added.\"\r\n\r\n\"(...) we adopt the betweenness of node i to estimate its load Li (...)We naturally assume that the capacity of node i, denoted as Ci, is proportional to its original load Li(0)\"\r\n\r\n\"[CASCADING PROCESS]  The dynamic process of the cascading failures is described as follows:\r\nStep 1: The node with the highest load is removed from the interconnected networks.\r\nStep 2: Recalculate the betweenness of the remaining nodes as their current loads. Find overloaded nodes whose loads are greater than their capacities and remove them.\r\nStep 3: Repeat step 2 until all the remaining nodes’ loads are not greater than their capacities.\r\nStep 4: After cascading failures, record the number of nodes in the giant component, denoted as N′.\"\r\n\r\n\"Capacity: Ci = (1 + α)Li(0) (2) where α ≥ 0 is the redundancy parameter. In this paper, we focus on the effect of capacity redundancy disparity on the robustness of interconnected networks.\"\r\n\r\n\"As we can see, the cascades process in interconnected networks is similar to that in isolated networks. However, from\r\nthe viewpoints of the interconnectivity between two networks, it is more complicated. There are two opposite effects of interconnected links. For one thing, one network can help accommodate a portion of overloads in the other network by using its spare capacity, which helps suppress cascading failures. For the other, it is possible that cascading failures propagate from one network to the other, which may lead to more serious collapse [47]. Moreover, if two interconnected networks are different in capacity redundancy, the effects of two networks on the whole system will be different.\"\r\n\r\n\"[METRIC] In this section, we will explore the effects of αA and αB on the network robustness. To qualify the robustness of interconnected networks, we use the relative size of the giant component \"\r\n\"[METRIC] We denote SA (SB) as the number of nodes which belong to network A (B) and are in the giant component of the whole system after cascading failures.\"','journal'),(523,'Using interdependency matrices to mitigate targeted attacks on interdependent networks: A case study involving a power grid and backbone telecommunications networks','ScienceDirect','using-interdependency',2016,'[ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT]\r\nAnalysis of the interdependencies between interconnected critical infrastruc- tures can help enhance the robustness of the individual infrastructures as well as the overall interconnected infrastructures. One of the most studied interdependent critical infrastructure network scenarios is a power grid connected to a backbone telecommunications network. In this interdependent infrastructure scenario, the robustness of the entire system is usually analyzed in the context of cascading failure models in the power grid. However, this paper focuses on targeted attacks, where an attack on a telecommunications network node directly affects a connected power grid node, and vice versa. Cascading failures are outside the scope of this paper because the objective is to enhance the robustness of the interconnections between the infrastructures. In order to mitigate the impacts of targeted attacks on the interdependent infrastructures, three interdependency matrices for connecting the infrastructures are specified and analyzed. The analysis identifies the interdependency matrix that best reduces the impacts of targeted attacks and the propagation of failures between the infrastructures. Additionally, the impacts of interconnecting a power grid to different telecommunications networks, each with different susceptibilities to targeted attacks, is evaluated.','[ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT]\r\n\r\nsummary: \"This paper focuses on identifying critical nodes that are targeted by attacks. Whether or not a failure spreads and generates a cascading failure is beyond the scope of this paper. Instead, the focus is on protecting telecommunications and power grid networks from propagating failures. By identifying the appropriate models for interconnecting the two types of networks, it is possible to enhance their robustness. The primary goal of this paper is to use interdependency matrices to eval- uate and mitigate the impacts of the most dangerous attacks on a backbone telecommunications network interconnected with a power grid. Specifically, the backbone telecommunications network is targeted by sequential attacks that leverage betweenness centrality while the power grid is targeted simul- taneously by attacks based on degree centrality; this enables the robustness of  the interconnected networks to be measured.\"\r\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nstudies:\r\n- coupling\r\n- targeted attacks?\r\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\"[MODEL] In other words, a targeted attack on one node in the telecommunications network only damages the power grid node to which it is directly connected and the failure does not spread to other power grid nodes, and vice versa.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] this paper fo- cuses on a scenario where a failure in one node of a network leads to a failure in the dependent node in the other network.\"\r\n\r\n\"[MODEL] Each node in G1 depends on one, and only one, node in G2, and vice versa.\"\r\n\r\n\"The one-to-one nodal interconnections between two networks can be con- ditioned by a coupling weight p > 0. In this model, the consequences of a failure in one network on the other network depend on a diffusion process provided by the strengths of the interconnections between the nodes. Thus, depending on the coupling weight p, different diffusion processes can be ex- pressed in interdependent networks. When p = 0, there are no interactions between the networks [10]. However, if p < p∗, then the two networks are structurally distinguishable; on the other hand, if p > p∗, the two networks behave as a whole [17]. (...) The analysis of the effects of p on failure propagation is a topic for future research\"\r\n\r\n\"[DEFINITION] The p∗ value represents a structural transition point.\"\r\n\r\n\"[COUPLING] \r\n• High Centrality Dependency Matrix (BHC) denoted as a dependency by an interlink Si ↔ Ti and which defines a one-to-one correspondence between nodes in G1 and G2, i.e., high-centrality (low-centrality) nodes in G1 are connected to high-centrality (low-centrality) nodes in G2.\r\n• Low Centrality Dependency Matrix (BLC) denoted as a dependency by an interlink Si ↔ TN−i+1 and which defines a one-to-one correspon- dence between nodes in G1 and G2, i.e., high-centrality nodes in G1 are connected to low-centrality nodes in G2, and vice versa.\r\n• Random Interdependency Matrix (BRA) denoted as a dependency by an interlink Si ↔ Tj and which defines a random one-to-one correspon- dence between nodes in G1 and G2, i.e., nodes in G1 and G2 are con- nected randomly without their centrality measures being considered, thus generating a random pattern.\"\r\n\r\n\"[METRIC] Although several metrics have been proposed for assessing network ro- bustness (see, e.g., [25]), this work uses the average two-terminal reliability (ATTR) [11] as the network robustness metric.\"\r\n\r\n\"In the failure scenarios considered in this paper, the percentage of nodes removed P ranged from 1% to 70%.\"','journal');
